# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: assyria
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] A **series of massacres in Hakkari** in the years 1843 and 1846 of Assyrian Christians were carried out by the Kurdish emirs of Bohtan and Hakkari, Bedir Khan Beg and Nurullah Beg along with allied Assyrian tribes who were against the rule of Shimun XVII Abraham.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Smith, the population lost as a result of these events was between 10,000 and 15,000, of which around 10,000 were killed during the first campaign.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Another American missionary, Justin Perkins, estimated that approximately 7,000 Assyrians were killed in Tehoma alone in 1846.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] By the 19th century, the weakened Ottoman Empire had started losing control over Upper Mesopotamia.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The empire seemed on the brink of collapse when Muhammad Ali revolted in Egypt and took control of Syria.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] It was then that Kurdish Emirs found an opportunity to assert their independence.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Among them was Ibrahim Pasha, a Kurdish Emir whose dominion included a region extending from Diyarbakır to Aleppo, and who fought alongside Muhammad Ali against the Ottomans and their allies from the Shammar tribe in Jazira.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Despite the failure of Muhammad Pasha in his Syrian campaign, the events showed the vulnerability of the Ottomans and encouraged Kurdish aghas to try and increase their control in the region.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] British fears of another French attempt similar to Napoleon's Egyptian campaign contributed to an increase of British influence.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] As these events unfolded, the British appointed Hormuzd Rassam, an ethnic Assyrian archaeologist from Mosul, and brother-in-law of Britain's ambassador in the city, as a delegate to expand British influence to the areas of the independent Assyrian tribes.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] British and American Protestant missionaries, such as Justin Perkins and Asahel Grant, started visiting the area in the same period.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] They generally showed great sympathy to the Assyrian Christians.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The Kurds, however, were wary of them, and the Assyrians' hospitality towards the foreigners only increased their suspicion.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The "hostile intention of the Kurds towards the Assyrians" was well known to British officials." On 27 January 1842, Canning wrote to the foreign secretary, Lord Aberdeen, informing him that the "Nestorians" have been subdued by a "Kurdish Bey" acting in concert with the Ottomans.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] War broke out in Hakkari in 1839 between Nurullah, brother of the former Emir, who governed from Bash Qal'a, and Suleyman his nephew whose capital was in Gullamerk.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The Assyrians were also split in their allegiances, according to their distribution.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Most of them, including the Patriarch of the Church of the East Shimun XVII Abraham, supported Suleyman as the rightful successor to his father.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The conflict turned into a massacre when Nurullah defeated his opponent and retaliated by attacking Assyrian villages and the Patriarchate of Qudshanis in 1841.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] This led to a permanent rift in relations between the Kurds and Assyrians in general.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] However, not all Assyrians allied themselves with the Patriarch.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Some took advantage of his weakness to join Nurullah.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The region descended into another war after a disagreement between Vali of Mosul, Mohammed Pasha, and the Kurdish Agha Ismael Pasha of Amedi.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The latter resorted to Nurullah of Hakkari and Badr Khan, the ambitious emir of Buhtan.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The three formed an alliance and called Assyrians to join them.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The Patriarch however refused to do so after receiving promises from Mosul to protect them in case of the Kurds decided to retaliate again.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] War between the Kurds and Ottomans broke out in summer 1842.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The next months were particularly calm in Hakkari with the Kurds busy with the war in Mosul, and missionary Asahel Grant commenced building a large religious school in the Christian Assyrian town of Ashitha and provided it with Syriac books and scriptures from Mosul in September, 1842.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The Kurdish campaign ended the same month with failure, and the Assyrians were blamed for refusing to intervene in the war.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Rumours spread that Grant built a castle to be used against the Kurds, and Nurullah protested to the vali of Erzurum.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] In addition, Ibrahim Pasha of Mosul was also alarmed by the rumours and the increased missionary activities in the region.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] He described in a letter to the Porte how Grant and the Christians built a huge building containing at least 200 rooms.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] In early 1843, Nurullah sent for a meeting with the patriarch and the latter apologized using the weather, his religious duties, and the presence of a guest, the British missionary George Badger, as a pretence.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] It seemed that the patriarch made his decision after being convinced by Badger to distrust the Kurds and to request assistance from the English or the Porte if the Kurds were to attack.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Once Badger left, Nurullah renewed his alliance with the Badr Khan and Ismail Pasha, and requested permission from the Vali of Mosul to subjugate the Christians.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] In July 1843, the Kurdish alliance, along with Assyrians that were against the rule of Shimun XVII Abraham led by Badr Khan, attacked the Assyrians in Hakkari, destroyed their villages and killed many of them.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Many of those who participated in the massacres had taken advantage of the weak connections between the Assyrian tribes, and many were forced to leave their homes due to the massacre.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Hormuzd Rassam tried using his influence with the Vali of Baghdad Najib Pasha to pressure Badr Khan for the release of prisoners, which included close relatives of the Patriarch of the Church of the East who had in the meantime taken refuge in Mosul.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] His attempts only led to the release of about 150, one of whom was the sister of the patriarch, while the rest were distributed as war booty between Agha's and Mullahs.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] On August 3, Kurdish forces had succeeded in "subduing the tribes and it was reported that 'still the slaughter is not yet ended, and several who have attempted to flee have been murdered...'".
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Then the invaders had turned "against the district of Tiyari, where they had succeeded in occupying the villages and indulged in the cruelest acts against its people".
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Even "those who had not opposed the Kurdish invasion had been treated in the same way as the fighters." The patriarch's mother's body was chopped into four pieces.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Many women and young children "were taken captive to be sold as slaves." On 21 August 1843, the British consul Abbott reported on "the role of the Kurds" in the massacres of Assyrian tribes who attacked the Kurds first.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The "prime agitator for the attack from the frontier was the 'Shaik'" of the Kurds of Bradost".
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The Kurdish tribes were "marching in large numbers directly to the Assyrian provinces." According to the wali of Mosul, the number of Kurdish soldiers was estimated at 100,000, although the Assyrians themselves are said to have estimated it at 70,000.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The Kurdish soldiers were united from all across the Middle East.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] It was reported that the "killing and destruction continued apace.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The surviving men and women were forced to carry unbearable loads of booty for very long distances, while being lashed all along the way until they fell from torture and exhaustion".
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Ross wrote: "They were tortured in an awful manner to force them to expose what they call hidden treasures, while others were killing them just for entertainment and as sport and games'.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The tribes "were all but encircled and left with no safe route to escape" the slaughter.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Those that tried to flee had to take a route that passed through the hostile Kurds of Berwar.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] One group after another was caught and slaughtered "while trying to escape".
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] It is estimated by contemporary sources that the victims of the assault of 1843 numbered ten thousand, but according to Adoona, that figure "cannot represent the total victims of the attack".
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] A crucial event in the conflict was when Bedir Khan Beg's forces captured Malik Ismael.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] As Ismael lay severely wounded, he defiantly declared, "This arm has taken the lives of nearly twenty Kurds; and, had God spared me, as many more would have fallen by it!" Soon after, Bedr Khan Beg ordered his men to execute Ismael by beheading him and throwing his body into the river.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Ismael's wife and many Assyrians were taken prisoner.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] However, a few managed to escape by crossing the Upper Zab river and to avoid being chased, they destroyed the Lezan bridge behind them on the orders of Mar Shimun.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Another massacre was inflicted by Bedir Khan in 1846, even against those Assyrians who joined him in his first campaign of massacres in 1843.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Bedir Khan killed 7,000 Assyrians just in Botan.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] This massacre received international attention through western press; it also woke European politicians and public opinion to the plight of Christians.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] This led the European countries to pressure the Porte to intervene and stop the massacres.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] In 1844 George Percy Badger working with Mar Shimun put the losses at 4,000 Assyrians dead.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The Kurdish massacres were a precursor to the later incursions which ended both the autonomous status which the Assyrian tribes enjoyed, and that which the Kurds in the mountainous areas had as well.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] The government saw the communal conflict as an opportunity to overthrow the last Kurdish emirates in 1847, establishing direct control of the entire region.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] A battalion was sent to the region in 1847, and clashed with the Kurds in several battles that ended with the arrest of both Badr Khan and Nurullah, and their exile in the same year.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Later on, the Hakkari province was established and governed from Başkale.
[src:assyria/1843-and-1846-massacres-in-hakkari] Due to the massacres of 1843-1846 committed by the troops of the Kurdish leader Bedr Khan Beg against the independent Assyrian tribes, "the long-Iasting existence of the Assyrian people as an independent body" was ended.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] The **1974–1975 Shatt al-Arab conflict** consisted of armed cross-border clashes between Iran and Iraq.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] It was a major escalation of the Shatt al-Arab dispute, which had begun in 1936 due to opposing territorial claims by both countries over the Shatt al-Arab, a transboundary river that runs partly along the Iran–Iraq border.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] The conflict took place between April 1974 and March 1975, and resulted in over 1,000 total casualties for both sides combined, though the Iranians eventually came to hold a strategic advantage over the Iraqis.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] Open hostilities formally came to an end with the 1975 Algiers Agreement, in which Iraq ceded around half of the border area containing the waterway in exchange for Iran's cessation of support for Iraqi Kurdish rebels.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] Qajar Iran had repudiated the demarcation line established in the Persian Gulf by the Anglo-Ottoman Convention of 1913, and argued that the Iran–Iraq border in the Shatt al-Arab should be demarcated according to the thalweg principle.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] In 1934, the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq, encouraged by the United Kingdom, took Pahlavi Iran to the League of Nations, but the dispute was not resolved.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] In 1937, Iran and Iraq signed their first official boundary treaty, which established the waterway border on the eastern bank of the river and excluded a four-mile anchorage zone near Abadan—which was allotted to Iran—where the border ran along the thalweg.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] In 1958, Iraq's Hashemite monarchy was overthrown in a coup d'état known as the 14 July Revolution, which established the First Iraqi Republic.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] In 1968, another coup d'état—staged by the Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party and known as the 17 July Revolution—deposed the First Iraqi Republic and firmly established a Ba'athist regime in Iraq.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] Shortly afterwards, Iran sent a delegation of diplomats to Iraq in 1969, and when the erstwhile Iraqi government refused to proceed with negotiations over a new treaty, Iran withdrew the treaty of 1937.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] The Iranian abrogation of the 1937 treaty marked the beginning of a period of acute tension in Iran–Iraq relations.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] In 1973, a raid on the Iraqi embassy in Pakistan uncovered large-scale covert Iraqi involvement in the supply of weapons and funds to militants waging an insurgency against Iran and Pakistan in Balochistan, further heightening the tensions between Iran and Iraq.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] This period of tensions lasted until the 1975 Algiers Agreement.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] From March 1974 to March 1975, Iran and Iraq fought border skirmishes sparked over Iran's support of Iraqi Kurds, who were engaged in an insurgency against the Arab-majority Iraqi state for secession and the establishment of an independent Kurdish state.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] In 1975, the Iraqis launched a small military incursion into Iran, spearheaded with tank columns; this incursion was defeated by the Iranians, after which several other attacks took place.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] However, Iran had the world's fifth-largest military at the time and promptly defeated the Iraqi military with its air power, while continuing to frustrate the Iraqis domestically with its arming of Kurdish separatists alongside its erstwhile close allies: the United States and Israel.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] Some 1,000 people died as a result of the 1974–75 conflict around the Shatt al-Arab, and Iraq was ultimately unable to gain any advantage against Iran.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] Consequently, Iraq decided against continuing the conflict, and chose instead to make concessions to Iran to end the Kurdish rebellion.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] In the 1975 Algiers Agreement, Iraq made territorial concessions—including the Shatt al-Arab waterway—in exchange for normalized bilateral relations.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] In return for Iraq recognizing that the frontier on the waterway ran along the entire thalweg as per Iran's argument, the latter ended its support for Iraqi Kurdish guerrillas.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] On 17 September 1980, Iraq abrogated the 1975 Algiers Agreement after Iranian forces shelled a number of Iraqi border posts on 4 September following the 1979 Iranian Revolution, which overthrew the Shah and established an Islamic theocracy.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] Iraqi President Saddam Hussein claimed that the newly-established Islamic Republic of Iran had refused to abide by the stipulations of the Algiers Accords and Iraq therefore considered them null and void.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] Tensions began to run high between the two states as Iraq's ruling Ba'ath Party feared that Ruhollah Khomeini was attempting to export the Iranian Revolution to Iraq by inciting the latter's Shia-majority population into revolting against the secular and Arab nationalist government.
[src:assyria/1974-1975-shatt-al-arab-conflict] Five days later, the Iraqi military launched a major offensive and invaded Iran, sparking the Iran–Iraq War.
[src:assyria/1977-shia-uprising-in-iraq] The **1977 Shia protests in Iraq**, or the Safar uprising, were a series of demonstrations and riots against the Iraqi government in Karbala and Najaf Governorates, the demonstrations started on 4 February 1977 and finished on 9 February in the same year.
[src:assyria/1977-shia-uprising-in-iraq] Demonstrators had taken to the streets to demonstrate against the Iraqi government because they had blocked Arbaʽeen Pilgrimage.
[src:assyria/1977-shia-uprising-in-iraq] The Iraqi security forces killed and arrested many protesters and presented them to trial in a revolution court, the revolution court declared execution for eight demonstrators and life imprisonment for 16 demonstrators.
[src:assyria/1977-shia-uprising-in-iraq] On 17 July 1968 the Ba'athism took power in Iraq, Ba'athism is an Arab nationalist and Arab socialist ideology that promotes the development and creation of a unified Arab state.
[src:assyria/1977-shia-uprising-in-iraq] In 1977, Ba'athism attempted to ban an annual pilgrimage to Karbala as well as attempted to ban religious processions.
[src:assyria/1977-shia-uprising-in-iraq] This move sparked protests, with the pilgrimage transforming into the 1977 Safar uprising in holy shia cities.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] Saddam and his deputies believed that the riots had been inspired by the Iranian Revolution and instigated by Iran's government.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] The riots erupted in May 1979 and escalated in June—leading to thousands being tortured and killed in Najaf.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] The uprising subsided with the April 1980 arrest of the leader of Shia Iraqis, Muhammad Baqir al-Sadr and his subsequent execution.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] Al-Sadr's works attracted the ire of the Baath Party leading to repeated imprisonment where he was often tortured.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] Despite this, he continued his work after being released.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] When the Baathists arrested Ayatollah Al-Sadr in 1977, his sister Amina Sadr bint al-Huda made a speech in the Imam Ali mosque in Najaf inviting the people to demonstrate.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] Many demonstrations were held, forcing the Baathists to release Al-Sadr who was placed under house arrest.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] In 1979–1980, anti-Ba'ath riots arose in the Iraq's Shia areas by groups, who were working toward an Islamic revolution in their country.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] In the aftermath of Iran’s revolution, Iraq’s Shiite community called on Mohammad Baqir al-Sadr to be their “Iraqi Ayatollah Khomeini”, leading a revolt against the Ba'ath regime.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] Community leaders, tribal heads, and hundreds of ordinary members of the public paid their allegiance to al-Sadr.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] Protests then erupted in Baghdad and the predominantly Shiite provinces of the south in May 1979.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] For nine days, protests against the regime unfolded, but were suppressed by the regime.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] The cleric’s imprisonment led to another wave of protests in June after a seminal, powerful appeal from al-Sadr’s sister, Bint al-Huda.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] Further clashes unfolded between the security forces and protestors.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] Najaf was put under siege and thousands were tortured and executed.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] Muhammad Baqir al-Sadr was finally arrested on 5 April 1980 with his sister, Sayedah Bint al-Huda.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] They had formed a powerful militant movement in opposition to Saddam Hussein's regime.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] On 9 April 1980, Al-Sadr and his sister were killed after being severely tortured by their Baathist captors.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] Signs of torture could be seen on the bodies.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] The Baathists raped Bint Houda in front of her brother.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] An iron nail was hammered into Al-Sadr's head and he was then set on fire in Najaf.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] It has been reported that Saddam himself killed them.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] The Baathists delivered the bodies of Baqir Al-Sadr and Bintul Huda to their cousin Sayyid Muhammad al-Sadr.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] They were buried in the Wadi-us-Salaam graveyard in the holy city of Najaf the same night.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] His execution raised no criticism from Western countries because Al-Sadr had openly supported Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] The 1999 Shia uprising in Iraq (or *Second Sadr Uprising*) took place in Iraq in early 1999 following the killing of Mohammad Mohammad Sadeq al-Sadr by the then Ba'athist government of Iraq.
[src:assyria/1979-1980-shia-uprising-in-iraq] The protests and ensuing violence were strongest in the heavily Shia neighborhoods of Baghdad, as well as southern majority Shiite cities such as Karbala, Nasiriyah, Kufa, Najaf, and Basra.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The **1991 Iraqi uprisings** were ethnic and religious uprisings against Saddam Hussein's Ba'athist regime that were mainly led by Shia rebels and Kurds.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The uprisings lasted from March to April 1991 after a ceasefire following the end of the Gulf War.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The mostly uncoordinated insurgency was fueled by the perception that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein had become vulnerable to regime change.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] This perception of weakness was largely the result of the outcome of the Iran–Iraq War and the Gulf War, both of which occurred within a single decade and devastated the population and economy of Iraq.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Within the first two weeks, most of Iraq's cities and provinces fell to rebel forces.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Participants in the uprising were of diverse ethnic, religious and political affiliations, including military mutineers, Shia Islamists, Kurdish nationalists, Kurdish Islamists, and far-left groups.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Following initial victories, the revolution was held back from continued success by internal divisions as well as a lack of anticipated American and Iranian support.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Saddam's Sunni Arab-dominated Ba'ath Party regime managed to maintain control over the capital of Baghdad and soon largely suppressed the rebels in a brutal campaign conducted by loyalist forces spearheaded by the Iraqi Republican Guard.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] During the brief, roughly one-month period of unrest, tens of thousands of people died and nearly two million people were displaced.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] After the conflict, the Iraqi government intensified a prior systematic forced relocation of Marsh Arabs and the draining of the Mesopotamian Marshes in the Tigris–Euphrates river system.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The Gulf War Coalition established Iraqi no-fly zones over northern and southern Iraq, and the Kurdish opposition established the Kurdistan Region in Iraqi Kurdistan.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] During the Iran–Iraq War, Iran's supreme leader, Ruhollah Khomeini, called on Iraqi Shias to overthrow the Ba'ath government and establish an Islamic state.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Because of his incitement, many Shia Arabs were driven out of Iraq and some were recruited into armed militias backed by Iran, although the majority remained loyal to Iraq throughout the duration of the war.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] On February 15, 1991, President of the United States, George H.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Bush, made a speech targeting Iraqis via Voice of America radio.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] On the evening of February 24, four days before the Gulf War ceasefire was signed, the Voice of Free Iraq radio station, allegedly funded and operated by the CIA, broadcast a message to the Iraqi people telling them to rise up and overthrow Saddam.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The speaker on the radio was Salah Omar al-Ali, an exiled former member of the Ba'ath Party and the Ba'athist Revolutionary Command Council.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Many of the rebels in southern Iraq, where the uprisings began, were either demoralized soldiers of the Iraqi Army or members of anti-regime groups, in particular the Islamic Dawa Party and Supreme Council for the Islamic Revolution in Iraq (SCIRI).
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Iraqi armed forces were composed largely of Shia conscripts and contained substantial anti-regime elements, and thus many of the government's troops quickly switched sides and defected to the rebels.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The turmoil first began in the towns of Abu Al-Khaseeb and Az Zubayr, south of Basra, at the end of February.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] On March 1, 1991, one day after the Gulf War ceasefire, a T-72 tank gunner, returning home after Iraq's defeat in Kuwait, fired a shell into a gigantic portrait of Saddam Hussein hanging over Basra's main square and onlooking soldiers applauded.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The revolt in Basra was led at first by Muhammad Ibrahim Wali, an army officer who gathered a force of military vehicles to attack the government buildings and prisons in the city; he was backed by a majority of the population.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The uprising in Basra was entirely spontaneous and disorganised.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The news of this event and Bush's radio broadcasts encouraged the Iraqi people to revolt against the regime in the other towns and cities.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In Najaf, a demonstration near the city's great Imam Ali Shrine became a gun battle between army deserters and Saddam's security forces.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The rebels seized the shrine as Ba'ath Party officials fled the city or were killed; prisoners were freed from jails.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The uprising spread within days to all of the largest Shia cities in southern Iraq: Amarah, Diwaniya, Hilla, Karbala, Kut, Nasiriyah and Samawah.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Smaller cities were swept up in the revolution as well.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Many exiled Iraqi dissidents, including thousands of Iran-based Badr Brigades militants of SCIRI, crossed the borders and joined the rebellion.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] SCIRI concentrated their efforts on the Shia holy cities of Najaf and Karbala, alienating many people who did not subscribe to their Shia Islamist agenda and pro-Iranian slogans, for which SCIRI was later criticized by the Dawa Party.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Ranks of the rebels throughout the region included mutinous Sunni members of the military, leftists such as Iraqi Communist Party (ICP) factions, anti-Saddam Arab nationalists, and even disaffected Ba'athists.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Disastrously for them, all the diverse revolutionary groups, militias, and parties were united only in their desire for regime change as they had no common political or military program, no integrated leadership, and there was very little coordination between them.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Another wave of insurgency broke out shortly afterwards in the Kurdish populated northern Iraq.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Unlike the spontaneous rebellion in the South, the uprising in the North was organized by two rival Kurdish party-based militias: primarily the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) and to a lesser extent the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP).
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Additionally, the Assyrian Democratic Movement (ADM) served as the principle Assyrian opposition group, although the group was more active in the 1980s.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The ADM reported that the government displaced thousands of Assyrians in Kirkuk, as there were around 30,000 in the city prior to 1991.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In the north, the defection of the government-recruited Kurdish home guard militias, known as jash, gave a considerable force to the rebellion.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The rebellion in the north (Iraqi Kurdistan) erupted on March 5 in the town of Rania.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Entire units surrendered without much or any resistance, including the whole 24th Division which did not fire a single bullet.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In Sulaymaniyah, the rebels besieged and captured the regional headquarters of the dreaded Directorate of General Security secret police (years later, the building, known as Amna Suraka or "Red Security" in Kurdish, became a museum to the crimes of Saddam's regime).
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In a bloody revenge, they killed several hundred of captured Ba'athist officials and security officers without a trial; reportedly, over 900 security officers were killed at Sulaymaniyah.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Unlike in the south, the Kurdish rebellion was preceded by demonstrations with clear political slogans: democracy for Iraq and autonomy for Kurdistan.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] After Mosul was taken, Jalal Talabani proposed to march on the capital Baghdad.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] On March 7, in an effort to quiet the uprisings, Saddam Hussein offered the Shia and Kurd leaders shares in the central government in exchange for loyalty, but the opposing groups rejected the proposal.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] At the height of the revolution, the government lost effective control over 14 of Iraq's 18 provinces.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] However, the people of Baghdad remained largely passive, as the Dawa Party, the Communist Party, and the pro-Syrian Ba'ath splinter party had all failed to build underground structures in the capital.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] There was only a limited unrest in the Shia-populated vast slum of Saddam City while the rest of Baghdad remained calm.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Soon, regime loyalists regrouped and went on an offensive to reclaim the cities.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] They were helped by the fact that about half of tanks of the elite and politically reliable Republican Guard managed to escape from the Saddam-proclaimed "mother of all battles" in Kuwait and that the Guard headquarters units also survived the war.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In addition, the Gulf War ceasefire agreement of March 3 prohibited the Iraqi military's use of fixed-wing aircraft over the country, but allowed them to fly helicopters because most bridges had been destroyed.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The outgunned rebels had few heavy weapons and few surface-to-air missiles, which made them almost defenseless against helicopter gunships and indiscriminate artillery barrages when the Ba'athists responded to the uprisings with crushing force.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] There were several reports of chemical warfare attacks, including of a nerve agent being used during the assault on Basra.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Following an investigation, the United Nations (UN) found that there was no evidence that Iraq used chemical weapons to repress the uprisings, but did not rule out the possibility that Iraq could have used phosgene gas which would not have been detectable after the attack.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In the south, Saddam's forces quelled all but a scattering of the resistance by the end of March.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] On March 29, SCIRI leader Abdul Aziz al-Hakim conceded that Shia rebels withdrew from the cities and that fighting was limited to rural areas.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The Kurdish uprising in the north of the country collapsed even more quickly than it began.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] After ousting the Peshmerga from Kirkuk on March 29, the government tanks rolled into Dahuk and Irbil on March 30, Zakho on April 1, and Sulaymaniyah, the last important town held by the rebels, on April 3.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The advance of government forces was halted at Kore, a narrow valley near the ruins of Qaladiza, where a successful defense was held by the Kurds led by Massoud Barzani.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In a 1999 letter, Hoshyar Zebari, head of International Relations of the Kurdish Democratic Party, stated that the "KDP as a major Kurdish political party had led and participated in the Kudish spring uprisings of 1991 in Iraqi Kurdistan.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The uprising caused the collapse of Iraqi government military, security and administrative structure in the region...
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] When the Iraqi troops counter-attacked and regained control of Kirkut and other major cities there were rumors of Mujahedin units assisting iraqi troops...
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] However... these rumors happen to be untrue...
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The KDP can confirm that the Mujahedin were not involved in suppressing the Kurdish people neither during the uprising nor its aftermath." Sources also say the Mujahedin supported the Kurdish rebellion in Iran.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The death toll was high throughout the country.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The rebels killed many Ba'athist officials and officers.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In response, thousands of unarmed civilians were killed by indiscriminate fire from loyalist tanks, artillery and helicopters, and many historical and religious structures in the south were deliberately targeted under orders from Saddam Hussein.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Saddam's security forces entered the cities, often using women and children as human shields, where they detained and summarily executed or "disappeared" thousands of people at random in a policy of collective responsibility.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Many suspects were tortured, raped, or burned alive.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Many of the people killed were buried in mass graves.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Mass burial sites containing thousands of bodies have been uncovered since the fall of Saddam Hussein in April 2003.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Of the 200 mass graves the Iraqi Human Rights Ministry had registered between 2003 and 2006, the majority were in the South, including one believed to hold as many as 10,000 victims.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In 1991, over 200,000 Shia Arabs and 100,000 Marsh Arabs had died in southern Iraq due to the war.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Furthermore, over 100,000 Assyrians had fled Iraq.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In March and early April, nearly two million Iraqis, 1.5 million of them Kurds, escaped from strife-torn cities to the mountains along the northern borders, into the southern marshes, and to Turkey and Iran.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] By April 6, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNCHR) estimated that about 750,000 Iraqi Kurds had fled to Iran and 280,000 to Turkey, with 300,000 more gathered at the Turkish border.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The approach towards the refugee immigration was met with a different approach by Iran and Turkey.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Iran had opened its borders to the refugees, while Turkey first closed its borders and only opened its borders following international pressure and assurances of financial help to cope with the refugees.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Iran also received much less international help to cope with the crisis than Turkey, mainly due to their strained relations with the USA.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] According to accounts from international relief organizations cited by Nader Entassar, Turkey received more than seven times the amount of help per refugee, as Iran received.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Their exodus was sudden and chaotic with thousands of desperate refugees fleeing on foot, on donkeys, or crammed onto open-backed trucks and tractors.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Many were gunned down by Republican Guard helicopters, which deliberately strafed columns of fleeing civilians in a number of incidents in both the north and south.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Numerous refugees were also killed or maimed by stepping on land mines planted by Iraqi troops near the eastern border during the war with Iran.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Department of State and international relief organizations, between 500 and 1,000 Kurds died each day along Iraq's Turkish border.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] According to some reports, up to hundreds of refugees died each day along the way to Iran as well.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Beginning in March 1991, the U.S. and some of the Gulf War allies barred Saddam's forces from conducting jet aircraft attacks by establishing the no-fly zone over northern Iraq and provided humanitarian assistance to the Kurds.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] On April 17, U.S. forces began to take control of areas more than 60 miles into Iraq to build camps for Kurdish refugees; the last American soldiers left northern Iraq on July 15.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In the Yeşilova incident in April, British and Turkish forces confronted each other over the treatment of Kurdish refugees in Turkey.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Many Shia refugees fled to Syria, where thousands of them settled in the town of Sayyidah Zaynab.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In southeastern Iraq, thousands of civilians, army deserters, and rebels began seeking precarious shelter in remote areas of the Hawizeh Marshes straddling the Iranian border.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] After the uprising, the Marsh Arabs were singled out for mass reprisals, accompanied by ecologically catastrophic drainage of the Iraqi marshlands and the large-scale and systematic forcible transfer of the local population.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The Marsh Arab resistance was led by the Hezbollah Movement in Iraq (completely unrelated to the Hezbollah of Lebanon), which after 2003 became the Marsh Arabs' main political party.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] On July 10, 1991, the United Nations announced plans to open a humanitarian center at Lake Hammar to care for those hiding out in the southern marshlands, but Iraqi forces did not allow UN relief workers into the marshlands or the people out.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] A large scale government offensive attack against the refugees estimated 10,000 fighters and 200,000 displaced persons hiding in the marshes began in March–April 1992, using fixed-wing aircraft; a U.S.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Department of State report claimed that Iraq dumped toxic chemicals in the waters in an effort to drive out the opposition.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In July 1992, the government began trying to drain the marshlands and ordered the residents of settlements to evacuate, after which the army burned down their homes there to prevent them from returning.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] A curfew was also enforced throughout the south, and government forces began arresting and moving large numbers of Iraqis into detention camps in the central part of the country.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] At a special meeting of the UN Security Council on August 11, 1992, Britain, France, and the United States accused Iraq of conducting a "systematic military campaign" against the marshlands, warning that Baghdad could face possible consequences.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] On August 22, 1992, President Bush announced that the U.S. and its allies had established a second no-fly zone for any Iraqi aircraft south of the 32nd parallel to protect dissidents from attacks by the government, as sanctioned by UN Security Council Resolution 688.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In November 1993, Iran reported that as a result of the drainage of the marshlands, marsh Iraqis could no longer fish or grow rice and that over 60,000 had fled to Iran since 1991; Iranian officials appealed to the world to send aid to help the refugees.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] That same month, the UN reported that 40% of the marshlands in the south were drained, while unconfirmed reports surfaced that the Iraq army had used poisonous gas against villages near the border of Iran.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In March 1994, a team of British scientists estimated that 57% of the marshlands have been drained and that in 10 to 20 years the entire wetland ecosystem in southern Iraq will be gone.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In April 1994, the U.S. officials said Iraq was continuing a military campaign in Iraq's remote marshes.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Iraq saw further unrest in its Shia dominated provinces in early 1999 following the killing of Grand Ayatollah Mohammad Mohammad Sadeq al-Sadr by the government.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Like the 1991 uprisings, the 1999 uprising was violently suppressed.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In the north, fighting continued until October when an agreement was made for Iraqi withdrawal from parts of Iraq's Kurdish-inhabited region.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] This led to the establishment of the Kurdistan Regional Government and creation of a Kurdish Autonomous Republic in three provinces of northern Iraq.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Tens of thousands of Iraqi soldiers dug-in along the front, backed by tanks and heavy artillery, while the Iraqi government established a blockade of food, fuel, and other goods to the area.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Air Force continued to enforce a no-fly zone over northern Iraq since March 1991, to defend Kurds fleeing their homes in northern Iraq, the U.S. military also built and maintained several refugee camps in 1991.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] This general stalemate was broken during the 1994–1997 Iraqi Kurdish Civil War, when due to the PUK alliance with Iran, the KDP called in Iraqi support and Saddam sent his military into Kurdistan, capturing Erbil and Sulaymaniyah.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Iraqi government forces retreated after the U.S. intervened by launching missile strikes on southern Iraq in 1996.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] On January 1, 1997, the U.S. and its allies launched Operation Northern Watch to continue enforcing the no-fly zone in the north the day after Operation Provide Comfort was over.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The trial of 15 former aides to Saddam Hussein, including Ali Hassan al-Majid (also known as "Chemical Ali"), over their alleged role in the murder of 60,000 to 100,000 people during the 1991 suppression took place in Baghdad in 2007 and 2008.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The issue was also given much attention during the trial of Saddam Hussein.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Many Iraqi and American critics accused President George H.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Bush and his administration of encouraging and abandoning the rebellion after halting Coalition forces at Iraq's southern border with Kuwait at the end of the Gulf War.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Soon after the uprisings began, fears of a disintegrating Iraq led the Bush administration to distance itself from the rebels.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] American military officials downplayed the significance of the revolts and spelled out a policy of non-intervention in Iraq's internal affairs.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Department of State spokesman Richard Boucher said on March 6, "We don't think that outside powers should be interfering in the internal affairs of Iraq." On April 2, in a carefully crafted statement, U.S.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The Bush administration sternly warned Iraqi authorities on March 7 against the use of chemical weapons during the unrest, but equivocated use of helicopter gunships by the government.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The U.S. abandonment of the 1991 revolution was cited by many analysts as an explanation for the fact that the skeptical Iraqi Shia population did not welcome the U.S.-led coalition forces during the 2003 invasion of Iraq the way some officials of George W.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Bush administration had predicted before the war began, remaining reluctant to rise up against Saddam until Baghdad fell.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] In 2011, the U.S. ambassador to Iraq, James F.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Jeffrey, officially apologized to Iraqi politicians and southern tribal leaders for the U.S. inaction in 1991.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Adel Abdul Mahdi, a top Iraqi Shia political leader, commented: "At the least, from what we are facing now, this would have been a much better solution than the solution of 2003.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] The role of Iraq's people would have been fundamental, not like in 2003." A spokesman for a top Shia religious leader, Ayatollah Basheer Hussain Najafi, stated that "the apology of the U.S. has come too late, and does not change what happened.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Films that have used the southern rebellions as their subject include the 1999 film *Three Kings* by David O.
[src:assyria/1991-iraqi-uprisings] Russell, the 2008 film *Dawn of the World* by Abbas Fahdel, as well as the 1993 Frontline documentary *Saddam's Killing Fields* by Michael Wood.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The **2003 invasion of Iraq** was the first stage of the Iraq War.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion began on 20 March 2003 and lasted just over one month, including 26 days of major combat operations.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion was conducted by a United States-led coalition of mainly American, British, Australian, and Polish troops.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush and UK prime minister Tony Blair, the coalition aimed to disarm Iraq of weapons of mass destruction (WMDs)—nuclear, chemical, and biological weapons—and "free the Iraqi people" by deposing president Saddam Hussein, in turn ending his "support for terrorism".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Before the invasion, United Nations (UN) inspectors in Iraq had found no evidence of Iraqi WMDs; U.S. and British officials claimed they were still hidden, and posed an immediate threat to world peace.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion was strongly opposed by some long-standing U.S. allies, including Canada, France, Germany, and New Zealand.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 2004, UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan called the invasion illegal under international law, as a breach of the UN Charter.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 15 February 2003, there were worldwide protests against the anticipated invasion of Iraq, including a rally of three million people in Rome which was the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion began with an airstrike on the Presidential Palace in Baghdad on 20 March 2003.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The following day, coalition forces launched an incursion into Basra Governorate from their massing point close to the Iraqi–Kuwaiti border.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] While special forces launched an amphibious assault from the Persian Gulf to secure Basra and the surrounding petroleum fields, the main invasion army occupied southern Iraq, engaging in the Battle of Nasiriyah on 23 March.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Massive air strikes across the country and against Iraqi command and control threw the defending army into chaos and prevented an effective resistance.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 26 March, the 173rd Airborne Brigade was airdropped near the northern city of Kirkuk, where they joined forces with Kurdish rebels and fought several actions against the Iraqi Army, to secure the northern part of the country.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The main body of coalition forces continued their drive into the heart of Iraq and were met with little resistance.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Most of the Iraqi military was quickly defeated.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 9 April 2003, 22 days after the first day of the invasion, the capital city of Baghdad was captured by coalition forces after the six-day-long Battle of Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Other operations included the capture and occupation of Kirkuk on 10 April and the attack on and capture of Tikrit on 15 April.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Saddam and the Iraqi central leadership went into hiding, as the coalition forces finished occupying the country.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 1 May, Bush declared the "end of major combat operations" in Iraq; this began the occupation phase of the Iraq War, in which coalition forces fought the Iraqi insurgency.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Saddam was captured by U.S. forces on 13 December 2003.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Gulf War began in 1990, and ended in 1991 with a ceasefire between the United Nations coalition and Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The U.S. and its allies tried to keep Saddam Hussein in check with military actions such as Operation Southern Watch, by monitoring and controlling some Iraqi airspace, as well as using economic sanctions.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Violating the Biological Weapons Convention, Iraq's biological weapons (BW) program began in the early 1980s, with help from the U.S. and European countries reportedly unaware of Iraq's intentions.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Details of Iraqi biological and chemical weapons program surfaced after the Gulf War, following investigations by the UN Special Commission (UNSCOM), which had been charged with the post-war disarmament of Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The investigation concluded that the program had not continued after the war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Iraqi military helicopters and planes regularly contested the no-fly zones.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 1998, regime change in Iraq became official U.S. foreign policy with enactment of the Iraq Liberation Act, enacted following the expulsion of UN weapons inspectors months earlier (some had been accused of spying for the U.S.).
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] One month later, the U.S. and UK bombed Iraq during Operation Desert Fox, their rationale being to hamper Iraq's ability to produce chemical, biological, and nuclear weapons, but U.S. intelligence personnel also hoped it would help weaken Saddam's grip on power.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush's inauguration in January 2001, the U.S. moved towards a more aggressive policy toward Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Republican Party's 2000 campaign platform called for the U.S. to "remove" Saddam.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] After leaving the Bush administration, Treasury Secretary Paul O'Neill said that an attack on Iraq had been planned since Bush's inauguration, and that the first U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] National Security Council meeting involved discussion of an invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] O'Neill later backtracked, saying that these discussions were part of a continuation of foreign policy first put into place by the Clinton administration.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Despite the Bush administration's stated interest in invading Iraq, little formal movement towards an invasion occurred until the 11 September attacks (9/11).
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On the morning of 11 September 2001, the al-Qaeda militant organization, led by Osama bin Laden, committed four coordinated terrorist attacks on the U.S., using hijacked commercial airliners to crash into major symbols of American economic and military power.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Messages intercepted by the National Security Agency during the attacks pointed to al-Qaeda's responsibility for them.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] By mid-afternoon, however, Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld ordered the Pentagon to prepare plans for attacking Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to aides near him that day, Rumsfeld messaged: "Best info fast.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Judge whether good enough hit S.H. [Saddam Hussein] at same time.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 12 September, Bush ordered White House counter-terrorism coordinator Richard A.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Clarke to investigate possible Iraqi involvement in 9/11.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Shocked by the sophistication of the attacks, the administration wondered whether a state sponsor was involved.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Clarke's office issued a memo on 18 September that noted wide ideological gaps between Iraq and al-Qaeda, and that only weak anecdotal evidence linked the two.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] However, U.S. vice president Dick Cheney and Rumsfeld expressed skepticism toward's the CIA's intelligence.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] They questioned whether the CIA were competent enough to produce accurate information as the agency underestimated threats and failed to accurately predict events such as the 1979 Iranian Revolution, the 1990 Iraqi invasion of Kuwait, and the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] They instead preferred outside analysis, of which information was supplied by the Iraqi National Congress as well as unvetted pieces of intelligence.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This information alleged that a highly secretive relationship existed between Saddam and al-Qaeda from 1992, specifically through a series of meetings reportedly involving the Iraqi Intelligence Service (IIS).
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The rationale for invading Iraq as a response to 9/11 has been widely questioned, as there was no cooperation between Saddam and al-Qaeda.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 20 September 2001, Bush addressed a joint session of Congress (telecast live to the world), and announced his new "war on terror".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This announcement was accompanied by the doctrine of "pre-emptive" military action, later termed the Bush Doctrine.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 21 November, Bush spoke with Rumsfeld and instructed him to conduct a confidential review of OPLAN 1003, the war plan for invading Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Rumsfeld met with General Tommy Franks, the commander of U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Central Command (CENTCOM), on 27 November to go over the plans.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A record of the meeting includes the question "How start?", listing multiple possible justifications for a U.S.–Iraq War.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Some Bush advisers favored an immediate invasion of Iraq, while others advocated building an international coalition and obtaining UN authorization.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush eventually decided to seek UN authorization, while still reserving the option of invading without it.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Also that day, Benjamin Netanyahu testified before the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congress, using expert testimony to encourage an invasion, and stating there was "no question" that Saddam was working on WMDs.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The UK agreed with the U.S. actions, while France and Germany were critical of plans to invade Iraq, arguing instead for continued diplomacy and weapons inspections.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] After considerable debate, the UNSC adopted a compromise resolution, UNSC Resolution 1441, which authorized the resumption of weapons inspections and promised "serious consequences" for non-compliance.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] UNSC members France and Russia made clear that they did not consider these consequences to include the use of force to overthrow the Iraqi government.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Both the U.S. ambassador to the UN, John Negroponte, and the UK ambassador, Jeremy Greenstock, publicly confirmed this reading of the resolution, assuring that Resolution 1441 provided no "automaticity" or "hidden triggers" for an invasion without further consultation of the UNSC.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Resolution 1441 gave Iraq "a final opportunity to comply with its disarmament obligations" and set up inspections by the UN Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC) and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Saddam accepted the resolution on 13 November and inspectors returned to Iraq under the direction of UNMOVIC chairman Hans Blix and IAEA Director-General Mohamed ElBaradei.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As of February 2003, the IAEA "found no evidence or plausible indication of the revival of a nuclear weapons program in Iraq"; the IAEA concluded that certain items which could have been used in nuclear enrichment centrifuges, such as aluminum tubes, were in fact intended for other uses.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] UNMOVIC "did not find evidence of the continuation or resumption" of WMD programs, or significant quantities of proscribed items.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Shortly before the invasion, UNMOVIC stated that it would take "months" to verify Iraqi compliance with resolution 1441.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congress passed the Iraq Resolution, which authorized the President to "use any means necessary" against Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Americans polled in January 2003 widely favored further diplomacy over an invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Later that year, however, Americans began to agree with Bush's plan.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The U.S. government engaged in an elaborate domestic public relations campaign to market the war to its citizens.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Americans overwhelmingly believed Saddam did have WMDs: 85% said so, even though the inspectors had not uncovered those weapons.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Of those who thought Iraq had weapons sequestered somewhere, about half responded that said weapons would not be found in combat.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] By February 2003, 64% of Americans supported taking military action to remove Saddam from power.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In the 2003 State of the Union address, Bush said "we know that Iraq, in the late 1990s, had several mobile biological weapons labs".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Secretary of State Colin Powell addressed the UNSC, continuing U.S. efforts to gain UN authorization for an invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] His presentation contained a computer-generated image of a "mobile biological weapons laboratory".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] However, this information was based on claims of Rafid Ahmed Alwan al-Janabi, codenamed "Curveball", an Iraqi emigrant living in Germany who later admitted that his claims had been false.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Powell falsely alleged that Iraq had ties to al-Qaeda.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As a follow-up to the presentation, the U.S., UK, Poland, Italy, Australia, Denmark, Japan, and Spain proposed a resolution authorizing the use of force in Iraq, but Canada, France, Germany, and Russia strongly urged continued diplomacy.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Facing a losing vote as well as a likely veto from France and Russia; the aforementioned countries eventually withdrew their resolution.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Opposition to the invasion coalesced in the worldwide 15 February 2003 anti-war protest that attracted between six and ten million people in more than 800 cities, the largest such protest in human history.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 16 March 2003, Spanish Prime Minister José María Aznar, UK Prime Minister Tony Blair, Bush, and Prime Minister of Portugal José Manuel Durão Barroso as host met in the Azores to discuss the invasion of Iraq and Spain's potential involvement in the war, as well as the beginning of the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This encounter was extremely controversial in Spain, even now remaining a very sensitive point for the Aznar government.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 2004, Madrid suffered the worst terrorist attack in Europe since the Lockerbie bombing, motivated by Spain's decision to participate in the war, prompting some Spaniards to accuse the Prime Minister of being responsible.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In March 2003, the U.S., UK, Poland, Australia, Spain, Denmark preparing for the invasion of Iraq, with a host of public relations and military moves.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In his 17 March address to the nation, Bush demanded that Saddam and his two sons, Uday and Qusay, surrender and leave Iraq, giving them a 48-hour deadline.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The UK House of Commons held a debate on going to war on 18 March where the government motion was approved 412 to 149.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The vote was a key moment in the history of the Blair administration, as the number of government MPs who rebelled against the vote was the greatest since the repeal of the Corn Laws in 1846.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Three government ministers resigned in protest at the war, John Denham, Lord Hunt of Kings Heath, and the then Leader of the House of Commons Robin Cook.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In December 2002, a representative of Iraqi General Tahir Jalil Habbush al-Tikriti, contacted former CIA Counterterrorism Department head Vincent Cannistraro, and stated that Saddam "knew there was a campaign to link him to 11 September and prove he had [WMDs]".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Cannistraro added that "the Iraqis were prepared to satisfy these concerns.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] I reported the conversation to senior levels of the state department and I was told to stand aside and they would handle it." Cannistraro stated that the offers made were all "killed" by the Bush administration because they allowed Saddam to remain in power, an outcome viewed as unacceptable.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] It has been suggested that Saddam was prepared to go into exile if allowed to keep U.S.$1 billion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Egyptian president Hosni Mubarak's national security advisor, Osama El-Baz, sent a message to the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] State Department that the Iraqis wanted to discuss the accusations that the country had WMDs and ties with al-Qaeda.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Iraq also attempted to reach the U.S. through the Syrian, French, German, and Russian intelligence services.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In January 2003, Lebanese-American Imad Hage met with U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Department of Defense official Michael Maloof.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Hage, a resident of Beirut, had been recruited by the department to assist in the war on terror.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He reported that Mohammed Nassif, a close aide to Syrian president Bashar al-Assad, had expressed frustrations about the difficulties of Syria contacting the U.S., and had attempted to use him as an intermediary.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Maloof arranged for Hage to meet with Richard Perle, then head of the Defense Policy Board.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In January 2003, Hage met with Iraqi intelligence official Hassan al-Obeidi.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Al-Obeidi told Hage that Baghdad did not understand why they were targeted and that they had no WMDs.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He then made the offer for Washington to send in 2000 FBI agents to confirm this.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He additionally offered petroleum concessions but stopped short of having Saddam give up power, instead suggesting that elections could be held in two years.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Later, al-Obeidi suggested that Hage travel to Baghdad for talks; he accepted.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Later that month, Hage met with General Habbush and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] They also wished to meet with high-ranking U.S. officials.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 19 February, Hage faxed Maloof his report of the trip.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Maloof reports having brought the proposal to Jaymie Duran.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Pentagon denies that either Wolfowitz or Rumsfeld, Duran's bosses, were aware of the plan.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 21 February, Maloof informed Duran in an email that Richard Perle wished to meet with Hage and the Iraqis if the Pentagon would clear it.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Keep this close hold." On 7 March, Perle met with Hage in Knightsbridge, and stated that he wanted to pursue the matter further with people in Washington, D.C.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A few days later, he informed Hage that Washington refused to let him meet with Habbush to discuss the offer (Hage stated that Perle's response was "that the consensus in Washington was it was a no-go").
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Throughout 2002, the Bush administration insisted that removing Saddam from power to restore international peace and security was a major goal.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The principal stated justifications for this policy of "regime change" were that Iraq's continuing production of WMDs and known ties to terrorist organizations, as well as Iraq's continued violations of UNSC resolutions, amounted to a threat to the U.S. and the world community.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush, speaking in October 2002, said that "The stated policy of the United States is regime change. ...
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Bush administration's overall rationale for the invasion of Iraq was presented in detail by Powell to the UNSC.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In September 2002, Blair stated that "Regime change in Iraq would be a wonderful thing.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] That is not the purpose of our action; our purpose is to disarm Iraq of weapons of mass destruction..." In November of that year, Blair further stated that, "So far as our objective, it is disarmament, not regime change – that is our objective.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As Blair made clear in a statement to the House of Commons, "I detest his regime.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] But even now he can save it by complying with the UN's demand.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In September 2002, the Bush administration said attempts by Iraq to acquire thousands of high-strength aluminum tubes pointed to a clandestine program to make enriched uranium for nuclear bombs.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Powell referred to the tubes in his UNSC presentation.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A report released by the Institute for Science and International Security in 2002, however, reported that it was highly unlikely that the tubes could be used to enrich uranium.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Bush administration asserted that the Saddam government had sought to purchase yellowcake uranium from Niger.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 7 March 2003, the U.S. submitted intelligence documents as evidence to the International Atomic Energy Agency.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These documents were dismissed by the IAEA as forgeries, with the concurrence in that judgment of outside experts.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the time, an American official stated that the evidence was submitted to the IAEA without knowledge of its provenance and characterized any mistakes as "more likely due to incompetence not malice".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Since the invasion, the U.S. government statements concerning Iraqi weapons programs and links to al-Qaeda have been discredited, though chemical weapons were found in Iraq during the occupation period.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] While the debate of whether Iraq intended to develop chemical, biological, and nuclear weapons in the future remains open, no WMDs have been found in Iraq since the invasion despite comprehensive inspections lasting more than 18 months.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In Cairo, on 24 February 2001, Powell had predicted as much, saying, "[Saddam] has not developed any significant capability with respect to weapons of mass destruction.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Another justification included the alleged connection between Saddam's and that of terrorist organizations such as al-Qaeda.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] While it never made an explicit connection between Iraq and 9/11, the Bush administration repeatedly insinuated a link, thereby creating a false impression for the U.S. public.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Grand jury testimony from al-Qaeda's 1993 World Trade Center bombing trials cited numerous direct connections between the bombers to Hussein's government.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Iraqi National Congress alleged that Saddam had been collaborating with al-Qaeda since 1992 via the Iraqi Intelligence Service (IIS).
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Steven Kull, director of the Program on International Policy Attitudes (PIPA), observed in March 2003 that the administration "has succeeded in creating a sense that there is some connection" between 9/11 and Saddam.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This was after a *New York Times*/CBS poll showed that 45% of Americans believed Saddam was "personally involved" in the attacks.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] And we know that after September 11, Saddam Hussein's regime gleefully celebrated the terrorist attacks on America." The BBC noted the results of a recent poll which suggested that 70% of Americans believe Saddam "was personally involved" in 9/11.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Since the invasion, assertions of operational links between Iraq and al-Qaeda have largely been discredited by the intelligence community, and Powell himself later admitted he had no proof of it.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In October 2002, a few days before the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Powell suggested in his 2003 UN presentation that UAVs were transported out of Iraq and could be launched against the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In actuality, Iraq had no offensive UAV fleet or any capability of putting UAVs on ships.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Iraq's UAV fleet consisted of less than a handful of outdated Czech training drones.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the time, there was a large dispute within the intelligence community whether the CIA's conclusions about the UAV fleet were accurate.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Air Force denied outright that Iraq had any offensive UAV capabilities.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Additional justifications used at various times included Iraqi violation of UN resolutions, the Iraqi government's repression of its citizens, and Iraqi violations of the 1991 ceasefire.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As evidence supporting American and British claims about Iraqi WMDs and links to terrorism weakened, some supporters of the invasion have increasingly shifted their justification to the human rights violations of the Saddam government.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Iraq Resolution of 2002 was passed by Congress with Republicans voting 98% in favor in the Senate, and 97% in favor in the House.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Democrats supported the joint resolution 58% and 39% in the Senate and House respectively.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The resolution asserted the authorization by the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Constitution and Congress for Bush to fight anti-American terrorism.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Citing the Iraq Liberation Act, the resolution reiterated that it should be the policy of the U.S. to depose Saddam's government and promote a democratic replacement.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Armed Forces "as he determines to be necessary and appropriate", to "defend [American] national security ... against the continuing threat posed by Iraq".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The legality of the invasion of Iraq under international law has been challenged since its inception on a number of fronts, and several prominent supporters of the invasion in all the invading states have publicly and privately cast doubt on its legality.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] It has been argued by the U.S. and UK that the invasion was fully legal because authorization was implied by the UNSC.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] International legal experts, including the International Commission of Jurists, a group of 31 leading Canadian law professors, and the U.S.-based Lawyers Committee on Nuclear Policy, have denounced this rationale.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 20 November 2003, *The Guardian* alleged that Richard Perle, a senior member of the administration's Defense Policy Board Advisory Committee, conceded that the invasion was illegal, but still justified.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The UNSC passed nearly 60 resolutions on Iraq and Kuwait since Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Resolution 1441 was most prominent during the run-up to the war and formed the main backdrop for Powell's UNSC address.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the same time, U.S. officials advanced a parallel legal argument using the earlier resolutions, which authorized force in response to Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Under this reasoning, by failing to disarm and submit to weapons inspections, Iraq was in violation of UNSC Resolutions 660 and 678, and the U.S. could legally compel Iraq's compliance through military means.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 2006, Luis Moreno Ocampo, the lead prosecutor for the International Criminal Court, reported that he had received 240 separate communications regarding the legality of the war, many of which concerned British participation in the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congressman Dennis Kucinich announced U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] House Resolution 333 and three articles of impeachment against Cheney.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He charged Cheney with manipulating evidence for Iraqi WMDs, deceiving the public about Iraq's connection to al-Qaeda, and threatening aggression against Iran in violation of the UN Charter.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The original list prepared in March 2003 included 49 members.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Of those 49, only six besides the U.S. contributed troops to the invasion force (the UK, Australia, Poland, Spain, Portugal, and Denmark), and 33 provided some number of troops to support the occupation after the invasion was complete.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Six members have no military, meaning that they withheld troops completely.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Approximately 200,194 troops—148,000 American, 50,000 British, 2,000 Australian, and 194 Polish (GROM special forces)—were sent to Kuwait for the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion force was also supported by Iraqi Kurdish Peshmerga fighters, estimated to number upwards of 70,000.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In the latter stages of the invasion, 620 troops of the Iraqi National Congress opposition group were deployed to southern Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Canada discreetly contributed some military resources towards the campaign, such as personnel from the Royal Canadian Air Force who crewed American planes on missions in Iraq to train with the platforms, and eleven Canadian aircrew who manned AWACS aircraft.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Canadian official Eugene Lang stated that it was "quite possible" that Canadian forces indirectly supported the American operation.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to Lang, Canada's military strongly advocated to be involved in the Iraq War instead of the war in Afghanistan, and Canada mainly decided to keep its assets in the Gulf to maintain good relations with America.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] After the invasion, Canadian Brigadier General Walter Natynczyk served as Deputy Commanding General of the Multi-National Corps in occupied Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Plans to open a second front in the north were severely hampered when Turkey refused the use of its territory for such purposes.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In response to Turkey's decision, the U.S. dropped several thousand paratroopers from the 173rd Airborne Brigade into northern Iraq, a number significantly less than the 15,000-strong 4th Infantry Division that the U.S. originally planned to deploy to the northern front.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The number of personnel in the Iraqi military before the war was uncertain, but it was believed to have been poorly equipped.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The International Institute for Strategic Studies estimated the numbers: the Iraqi Armed Forces at 389,000 (Ground Forces 350,000, Air Force 20,000, Air Defense 17,000, and Navy 2,000), the paramilitary Fedayeen Saddam at 44,000, Republican Guard at 80,000, and reserves at 650,000.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] There were an estimated thirteen infantry divisions, ten mechanized and armored divisions, as well as some special forces units.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Iraqi Air Force and Navy played a negligible role in the conflict.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] During the invasion, foreign volunteers traveled to Iraq from Syria and took part in the fighting, usually commanded by the Fedayeen Saddam.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] It is not known for certain how many foreign fighters fought in Iraq in 2003, however, intelligence officers of the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] First Marine Division estimated that 50% of all Iraqi combatants in central Iraq were foreigners.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In addition, the Kurdish Islamist militant group Ansar al-Islam controlled a small section of northern Iraq in an area outside Saddam's control.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Ansar al-Islam had been fighting against secular Kurdish forces since 2001.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the time of the invasion they fielded about 600 to 800 fighters.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Ansar al-Islam was led by the Jordanian-born militant Abu Musab al-Zarqawi, who would later become an important leader in the Iraqi insurgency.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Ansar al-Islam was driven out of Iraq in late March by a joint American-Kurdish force during Operation Viking Hammer.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In the information, the American forces provided the Dutch Ministry of Defense with the GPS coordinates of the DU rounds, along with a list of targets and numbers fired.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Then, the Dutch Ministry of Defence released the data to Dutch peace group Pax under the Freedom of Information Act.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Coalition forces used 61,000 cluster munitions containing 20 million submunitions during the Gulf War, and 13,000 cluster munitions containing two million submunitions during the 2003 invasion and subsequent insurgency.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Thousands of unexploded munitions from the invasion and previous wars, including cluster munitions, mines and other unexploded ordnance, still posed a threat to civilians as of 2022.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] CIA Special Activities Division (SAD) and MI6 (E Squadron) paramilitary teams entered Iraq in July 2002 before the 2003 invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Once on the ground they prepared for the subsequent arrival of American and British military forces.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Army Special Forces to organize the Kurdish Peshmerga.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This joint team combined to defeat Ansar al-Islam, an ally of Al Qaeda, in a battle in the northeast corner of Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A chemical weapons facility at Sargat was also captured.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Sargat was the only facility of its type discovered in the Iraq war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The U.S. side was carried out by Paramilitary Officers from SAD and the Army's 10th Special Forces Group.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] SAD teams also conducted high-risk special reconnaissance missions behind Iraqi lines to identify senior leadership targets.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These missions led to the initial strikes against Saddam Hussein and his key generals.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Although the initial strikes against Saddam were unsuccessful in killing the dictator or his generals, they were successful in effectively ending the ability to command and control Iraqi forces.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Other strikes against key generals were successful and significantly degraded the command's ability to react to and maneuver against the U.S.-led invasion force coming from the south.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] SAD operations officers were also successful in convincing key Iraqi army officers to surrender their units once the fighting started or not to oppose the invasion force.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] NATO member Turkey refused to allow its territory to be used for the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Army Special Forces joint teams and the Kurdish Peshmerga constituted the entire northern force against government forces during the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Their efforts kept the 5th Corps of the Iraqi army in place to defend against the Kurds rather than moving to contest the coalition force in the south.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Four of these CIA officers were awarded the Intelligence Star for their actions.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] MI6 conducted Operation Mass Appeal which was a campaign to plant stories about Iraq's WMDs in the media and boost support for the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] MI6 also went on to bribe many of Saddam's closest allies to turn over information and intelligence.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to Tommy Franks, "April Fool", an American officer working undercover as a diplomat, was approached by an Iraqi intelligence agent.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] April Fool then sold the Iraqi false "top secret" invasion plans provided by Franks' team.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This deception misled the Iraqi military into deploying major forces in northern and western Iraq in anticipation of attacks by way of Turkey or Jordan, which never took place.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This greatly reduced the defensive capacity in the rest of Iraq, and facilitated the actual attacks via Kuwait and the Persian Gulf in the southeast.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Since the Gulf War, the U.S. and UK had been attacked by Iraqi air defenses while enforcing Iraqi no-fly zones.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These zones, and the attacks to enforce them, were described as illegal by the former UN Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali, and the French foreign minister Hubert Vedrine.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Other countries, notably Russia and China, also condemned the zones as a violation of Iraqi sovereignty.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In mid-2002, the U.S. began more carefully selecting targets in the southern part of the country to disrupt the military command structure in Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A change in enforcement tactics was acknowledged at the time, but it was not made public that this was part of a plan known as Operation Southern Focus.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The amount of ordnance dropped on Iraqi positions by coalition aircraft in 2001 and 2002 was less than in 1999 and 2000 which was during the Clinton administration.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] However, information obtained by the UK Liberal Democrats showed that the UK dropped twice as many bombs on Iraq in the second half of 2002 as they did during the whole of 2001.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The tonnage of UK bombs dropped increased from 0 in March 2002 and 0.3 in April 2002 to between 7 and 14 tons per month in May–August, reaching a pre-war peak of 54.6 tons in September – before the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congress' 11 October authorization of the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The 5 September attacks included a 100+ aircraft attack on the main air defense site in western Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to an editorial in *New Statesman* this was "located at the furthest extreme of the southern no-fly zone, far away from the areas that needed to be patrolled to prevent attacks on the Shias.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Tommy Franks, who commanded the invasion, has since admitted that the bombing was designed to "degrade" Iraqi air defences in the same way as the air attacks that began the Gulf War.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These "spikes of activity" were, in the words of then-British Defence Secretary, Geoff Hoon, designed to 'put pressure on the Iraqi regime' or, as *The Times* reported, to "provoke Saddam Hussein into giving the allies an excuse for war".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In this respect, as provocations designed to start a war, leaked British Foreign Office legal advice concluded that such attacks were illegal under international law.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Another attempt at provoking the war was mentioned in a leaked memo from a meeting between Bush and Blair on 31 January 2003, in which Bush allegedly told Blair that "The U.S. was thinking of flying U2 reconnaissance aircraft with fighter cover over Iraq, painted in UN colours.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] If Saddam fired on them, he would be in breach." On 17 March, Bush gave Saddam 48 hours to leave the country, along with his sons Uday and Qusay, or face war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On the night of 17 March 2003, the majority of B and D squadron British 22nd SAS Regiment, designated as Task Force 14, crossed the border from Jordan to conduct a ground assault on a suspected chemical munitions site at a water-treatment plant in the city of al-Qa'im.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Following their insertion, D squadron established a patrol laager at a remote location outside al-Qa'im and awaited the arrival of B squadron, who had driven overland from Jordan.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Their approach to the plant was compromised, and a firefight developed which ended in one 'pinkie' having to be abandoned and destroyed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Repeated attempts to assault the plant were halted, leading the SAS to call in an air strike which silenced the opposition.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In the early morning of 19 March, U.S. forces abandoned the plan for initial, non-nuclear decapitation strikes against 55 top Iraqi officials, in light of reports that Saddam was visiting Uday and Qusay at Dora Farms, in the Dora farming community in southern Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At approximately 04:42 Baghdad time, two F-117 Nighthawk stealth fighters from the 8th Expeditionary Fighter Squadron dropped four enhanced, satellite-guided 2,000-pound GBU-27 'Bunker Busters' on the compound.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] One bomb missed the compound entirely, while the other three impacted the site on the other side of an electrified wall surrounding the main palace building, damaging it and destroying every other structure in the compound.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Saddam was not present, nor were any members of the Iraqi leadership.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Baghdad-area hospitals reported that the attack killed one civilian and injured fourteen others, including four men, nine women and one child.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Later sources indicated that Saddam had not visited the farm since 1995, while others claimed that Saddam *had* been at the compound that morning, but had left before the strike, which Bush had ordered delayed until the 48-hour deadline had expired.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Within seven hours, more than 70 sites were destroyed, effectively depriving the Iraqi military of any early warning of the coming invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] As the sites were eliminated, the first heliborne SOF teams launched from H-5 air base in Jordan, including vehicle-mounted patrols from the British and Australian components transported by the MH-47Ds of the 160th SOAR.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Ground elements of Task Force Dagger, Task Force 20, Task Force 14, and Task Force 64 breached the sand berms along the Iraqi border with Jordan, Saudi Arabia, and Kuwait in the early morning hours and drove into Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Unofficially, the British, Australians, and Task Force 20 had been in Iraq weeks prior.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 20 March at approximately 02:30 UTC, at 05:34 local time, explosions were heard in Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Special operations commandos from the CIA's Special Activities Division from the Northern Iraq Liaison Element infiltrated throughout Iraq and called in the early air strikes.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At 03:16 UTC, or 10:16 pm EST, Bush announced that he had ordered an attack against "selected targets of military importance" in Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] When this word was given, the troops on standby crossed the border into Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Before the invasion, many observers had expected a longer campaign of aerial bombing before any ground action, taking as examples the Gulf War or the 2001 invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In practice, U.S. plans envisioned simultaneous air and ground assaults to incapacitate the Iraqi forces quickly which resulted in the shock and awe military campaign attempting to bypass Iraqi military units and cities in most cases.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The assumption was that superior mobility and coordination of coalition forces would allow them to attack the heart of the Iraqi command structure and destroy it in a short time, and that this would minimize civilian deaths and damage to infrastructure.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] It was expected that the elimination of the leadership would lead to the collapse of Iraq's military and government, and that much of the population would support the invaders once the government had been weakened.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Occupation of cities and attacks on peripheral military units were viewed as undesirable distractions.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Following Turkey's decision to deny any official use of its territory, the coalition was forced to modify the planned simultaneous attack from north and south.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Special Operations forces from the CIA and U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army managed to build and lead the Kurdish Peshmerga into an effective force and assault for the North.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The primary bases for the invasion were in Kuwait and other Persian Gulf states.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] One result of this was that one of the divisions intended for the invasion was forced to relocate and was unable to take part in the invasion until well into the war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Iraqis immediately adapted to the invasion, and began using unconventional tactics.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 22 March, American troops first encountered the insurgency tactics that would later define the war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] 1st Class Anthony Broadhead, a platoon sergeant in the Crazy Horse troop of the 3rd Infantry Division's cavalry unit, was in a tank heading towards a bridge in Samawah on the invasion route.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] He waved at a group of Iraqis, but instead of waving back, they began attacking the American tanks with AK-47 rifles, rocket-propelled grenades, and mortars.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Because these types of paramilitary forces were well-armed, but indistinguishable from civilians, they would come to pose a significant challenge for U.S. forces throughout Iraq War.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The invasion itself was swift, leading to the collapse of the Iraqi government and the military of Iraq in about three weeks.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The oil infrastructure of Iraq was rapidly seized and secured with limited damage in that time.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Securing the oil infrastructure was considered of great importance.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Before the invasion, Iraqi forces had mined some 400 oil wells around Basra and the Al-Faw peninsula with explosives.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Coalition troops launched an air and amphibious assault on the Al-Faw peninsula during the closing hours of 19 March to secure the oil fields there; the amphibious assault was supported by warships of the Royal Navy, Polish Navy, and Royal Australian Navy.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 1 April, an F-14 from USS *Kitty Hawk* crashed in southern Iraq reportedly due to engine failure, and a S-3B Viking plunged off the deck of the USS *Constellation* after a malfunction and an AV-8B Harrier jump jet went into the Gulf while it was trying to land on the USS *Nassau*.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The British 3 Commando Brigade, with the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Navy's Special Boat Team 22, Task Unit Two, as well as the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Marine Corps' 15th Marine Expeditionary Unit and the Polish Special Forces unit GROM attached, attacked the port of Umm Qasr.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] There they met with heavy resistance by Iraqi troops.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A total of 14 coalition troops and 30–40 Iraqi troops were killed, and 450 Iraqis taken prisoner.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The British Army's 16 Air Assault Brigade alongside elements of the RAF Regiment also secured the oil fields in southern Iraq in places like Rumaila while the Polish commandos captured offshore oil platforms near the port, preventing their destruction.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Despite the rapid advance of the invasion forces, some 44 oil wells were destroyed and set ablaze by Iraqi explosives or by incidental fire.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] However, the wells were quickly capped and the fires put out, preventing the ecological damage and loss of oil production capacity that had occurred at the end of the Gulf War.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In keeping with the rapid advance plan, the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] 3rd Infantry Division moved westward and then northward through the western desert toward Baghdad, while the 1st Marine Expeditionary Force moved along Highway 1 through the center of the country, and 1 (UK) Armoured Division moved northward through the eastern marshland.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] During the first week of the war, Iraqi forces fired a Scud missile at the American Battlefield Update Assessment center in Camp Doha, Kuwait.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The missile was intercepted and shot down by a Patriot missile seconds before hitting the complex.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Subsequently, two A-10 Warthogs attacked the missile launcher.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Initially, the U.S.' 1st Marine Division fought through the Rumaila oil fields, and moved north to Nasiriyah—a moderate-sized, Shi'ite-dominated city with important strategic significance as a major road junction and its proximity to nearby Tallil Airfield.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] It was also situated near a number of strategically important bridges over the Euphrates River.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The city was defended by a mix of regular Iraqi army units, Ba'ath loyalists, and Fedayeen from both Iraq and abroad.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army 3rd Infantry Division defeated Iraqi forces entrenched in and around the airfield and bypassed the city to the west.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 23 March, a convoy from the 3rd Infantry Division, including the female American soldiers Jessica Lynch, Shoshana Johnson, and Lori Piestewa, was ambushed after taking a wrong turn into the city.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Eleven U.S. soldiers were killed, and seven, including Lynch and Johnson, were captured.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Piestewa died of wounds shortly after capture, while the remaining five prisoners of war were later rescued.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Piestewa, who was from Tuba City, Arizona, and an enrolled member of the Hopi Tribe, was believed to have been the first Native American woman killed in combat in a foreign war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Marines from the 2nd Marine Division entered Nasiriyah in force, facing heavy resistance as they moved to secure two major bridges in the city.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Several marines were killed during a firefight with Fedayeen in the urban fighting.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At the Saddam Canal, another 18 marines were killed in heavy fighting with Iraqi soldiers.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] An Air Force A-10 was involved in a case of friendly fire that resulted in the death of six Marines when it accidentally attacked an American amphibious vehicle.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Two other vehicles were destroyed when a barrage of RPG and small arms fire killed most of the Marines inside.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A Marine from Marine Air Control Group 28 was killed by enemy fire, and two Marine engineers drowned in the Saddam Canal.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The bridges were secured and the Second Marine division set up a perimeter around the city.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On the evening of 24 March, the 2nd Light Armored Reconnaissance Battalion, which was attached to Regimental Combat Team One (RCT-1), pushed through Nasiriyah and established a perimeter 15 km (9.3 miles) north of the city.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Iraqi reinforcements from Kut launched several counterattacks.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Marines managed to repel them using indirect fire and close air support.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The last Iraqi attack was beaten off at dawn.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The battalion estimated that 200–300 Iraqi soldiers were killed, without a single U.S. casualty.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Nasiriyah was declared secure, but attacks by Iraqi Fedayeen continued.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] These attacks were uncoordinated, and resulted in firefights that killed many Fedayeen.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Because of Nasiriyah's strategic position as a road junction, significant gridlock occurred as U.S. forces moving north converged on the city's surrounding highways.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] With the Nasiriyah and Tallil Airfields secured, coalition forces gained an important logistical center in southern Iraq and established FOB/EAF Jalibah, some 10 miles (16 km) outside Nasiriyah.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Additional troops and supplies were soon brought through this forward operating base.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The 101st Airborne Division continued its attack north in support of the 3rd Infantry Division.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] By 28 March, a severe sandstorm slowed the coalition advance as the 3rd Infantry Division halted its northward drive halfway between Najaf and Karbala.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Air operations by helicopters, poised to bring reinforcements from the 101st Airborne, were blocked for three days.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] There was particularly heavy fighting in and around the bridge near the town of Kufl.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Another fierce battle was at Najaf, where U.S. airborne and armored units with British air support fought an intense battle with Iraqi Regulars, Republican Guard units, and paramilitary forces.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] AH-64 Apache helicopter gunships setting out on a mission to attack Republican Guard armored units; while flying low the Apaches came under heavy anti-aircraft, small arms, and RPG fire which heavily damaged many helicopters and shot one down, frustrating the attack.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] They attacked again successfully on 26 March, this time after a pre-mission artillery barrage and with support from F/A-18 Hornet jets, with no gunships lost.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The 1st Brigade Combat Team's air defense battery supported by a COLT (combat observation lasing team) and the Brigade Recon Troop moved in to secure the bridge at Al Kifl late on 24 March.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] When the ADA company was unable to secure the western bank of the bridge the commander called for reinforcements.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Grimsley order LTC Marcone Task Force 3-69 Armor to send a quick reaction force to support the ADA company.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] LTC Marcone sent B 3-7 Infantry to clear and secure the bridge.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Bravo Company was made up of two infantry platoons with M2A2 Bradley Fighting Vehicles and one platoon of M1A2 Abrams tanks.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Bravo 3-7 Infantry secured the bridge and fought for 36 hours through a sandstorm.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] During that time, the soldiers fought against Iraqi Military and Fedayeen forces.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] After 36 hours, B co 3-7 Infantry was relieved on 26 March.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The 101st Airborne Division on 29 March, supported by a battalion from the 1st Armored Division, attacked Iraqi forces in the southern part of the city, near the Imam Ali Mosque and captured Najaf's airfield.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Four Americans were killed by a suicide bomber.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 31 March, the 101st made a reconnaissance-in-force into Najaf.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 1 April, elements of the 70th Armored Regiment launched a "Thunder Run", an armored thrust through Najaf's city center, and, with air support, defeated the Iraqi forces after several days of heavy fighting.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Iraqi port city of Umm Qasr was the first British obstacle.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A joint Polish-British-American force ran into unexpectedly stiff resistance, and it took several days to clear the Iraqi forces out.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Farther north, the British 7 Armoured Brigade, fought their way into Iraq's second-largest city, Basra, on 6 April, coming under constant attack by regulars and Fedayeen, while 3rd Battalion, The Parachute Regiment cleared the 'old quarter' of the city that was inaccessible to vehicles.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Entering Basra was achieved after two weeks of fierce fighting, including a tank battle when the Royal Scots Dragoon Guards destroyed 14 Iraqi tanks on 27 March.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A few members of D Squadron, British SAS, were deployed to southern Iraq to support the coalition advance on Basra.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The team conducted forward route reconnaissance and infiltrated the city and brought in strikes on the Ba'athist loyalist leadership.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Elements of 1 (UK) Armoured Division began to advance north towards U.S. positions around Al Amarah on 9 April.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Pre-existing electrical and water shortages continued throughout the conflict and looting began as Iraqi forces collapsed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] After a rapid initial advance, the first major pause occurred near Karbala.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army elements met resistance from Iraqi troops defending cities and key bridges along the Euphrates River.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] These forces threatened to interdict supply routes as American forces moved north.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Eventually, troops from the 101st Airborne Division of the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army secured the cities of Najaf and Karbala to prevent any Iraqi counterattacks on the 3rd Infantry Division's lines of communication as the division pressed its advance toward Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Eleven British soldiers were killed, while 395–515 Iraqi soldiers, irregulars, and Fedayeen were killed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The efforts of the British Army facilitated the re-establishment of the rail lines from the port to Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Karbala Gap was a 20–25-mile wide strip of land with the Euphrates River to the east and Lake Razazah to the west.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] This strip of land was recognized by Iraqi commanders as a key approach to Baghdad, and was defended by some of the best units of the Iraqi Republican Guard.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Iraqi high command had originally positioned two Republican Guard divisions blocking the Karbala Gap.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Here these forces suffered heavy coalition air attacks.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] However, the coalition had since the beginning of March been conducting a strategic deception operation to convince the Iraqis that the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] 4th Infantry Division would be mounting a major assault into northern Iraq from Turkey.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] As part of Task Force 20, their formal role was to conduct selected high-priority site exploitation on suspected chemical weapon facilities before heading for the Haditha Dam complex.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Along the way, Delta supported the seizure of H-3 Air Base and also conducted numerous deception operations to confuse the Iraqis as to the disposition of coalition forces in the west.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 18 March 2003, B and D Squadrons of the British 22nd SAS Regiment had now infiltrated Iraq in full strength (D Squadron by air and B Squadron by ground) along with 1 Squadron Australian SASR and headed for H-2 and H-3 Air Base.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] They set up observation posts and called in airstrikes that defeated the Iraqi defenders.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The combined British and Australian Squadrons took H-2 virtually unopposed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] H-3 was secured on 25 March with the assistance of members of Delta Force and by Green Beret ODAs from Bravo company, 1st Battalion 5th SFG; a company of Rangers and Royal Marines from 45 Commando flew from Jordan to the bases and the base was handed over to them.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The SAS teams moved to the next objective – the intersection of the two main highways linking Baghdad with Syria and Jordan, where both squadrons were involved in conducting interdictions of fleeing Iraqi leadership targets heading for Syria.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In northern Iraq in early March, a small reconnaissance team from M Squadron of the British Special Boat Service mounted on Honda ATVs inserted into Iraq from Jordan.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Its first mission was to conduct reconnaissance of an Iraqi air base at al-Sahara.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The team was compromised by an anti-special forces Fedayeen unit and barely escaped thanks to a U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] F-15E that flew air cover for the team and an RAF Chinook that extracted the team from out under the Fedayeen's "noses".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] However the Squadron was compromised by a goat herder; the SBS drove for several days while unknown to them anti-special forces Fedayeen units followed them.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At an overnight position near Mosul, the Fedayeen ambushed the Squadron with DShK heavy machine guns and RPGs, the SBS returned fire and began taking fire from a T-72, the Squadron scattered and escaped the well-constructed trap.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A number of Land Rovers became bogged down in a nearby wadi, so they mined the vehicles and abandoned them – though several did not detonate and were captured and exhibited on Iraqi television.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The SBS was now in three distinct groups: one with several operational Land Rovers was being pursued by the Iraqi hunter force, a second mainly equipped with ATVs was hunkered down and trying to arrange extraction, the third with just 2 operators on an ATV raced for the Syrian border.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The second group was also extracted by an RAF Chinook and the third group made it to Syria and was held there until their release was negotiated, there were no SBS casualties.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Viking Hammer was set to begin on 21 March, however, the ground component of the operation was set back several days owing to the issues around infiltrating most of the 3rd Battalion 10th SFG into Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Islamic Group of Kurdistan surrendered after having suffered 100 men killed in the 21 March strikes.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 28 March, the ground element of Operation Viking Hammer was finally launched with a six-pronged advance, each prong was composed of several ODAs from 3rd Battalion, 10th SFG and upwards of 1,000 Kurdish Peshmerga fighters.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The main advance set off towards Sargat – the location of the suspected chemical and biological weapons site; the force was soon pinned down by DShK heavy machine-gun fire from the surrounding hills.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Navy F/A-18s responded to an urgent CAS request from the force and dropped two 500lb JDAMs on the Ansar al-Islam machine gun nests and strafed the positions with 20 mm cannon before departing due to being low on fuel.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The advance began again only to be halted once more by fire from prepared DShK and PKM machine gun nests, Green Berets from ODA 081 deployed a Mk 19 grenade launcher from the back of a Toyota Tacoma and suppressed the gun positions allowing the Peshmerga to assault and wipe out the terrorists.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After capturing the town of Gulp, the force continued onto the village of Sargat; the village was heavily defended by fortified fighting positions mounting DShKs and mortars along with several BM-21 Grad.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Unable to call in airstrikes due to the close proximity of the Peshmerga, a Green Beret sergeant used a dismounted M2 HMG to suppress the entrenched terrorists, his actions allowed the Peshmerga to bring forward their own 82 mm Mortars and Grads which forced the Ansar al-Islam fighters to retreat.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] To dislodge the terrorists, the Combat Controllers attached to the ODAs vectored in U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Navy F/A-18s which dropped six 500 lb JDAMs that shut down any further resistance.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] With their objectives completed, the 3rd Battalion and their Peshmerga returned to the green line to assist the push on Kirkuk and Mosul.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A specialist SSE team was brought in to document the find at Sargat, the team recovered traces of several chemicals including Ricin along with stocks of NBC protective suits, atropine injectors and Arabic manuals on chemical weapons and IED construction.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Estimates of Ansar al-Islam dead number over 300, many of them foreign fighters, while only 22 Peshmerga fighters were killed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Turkey had officially prohibited any coalition troops from using their bases or airspace, so lead elements of the 10th SFG had to make a detour infiltration; their flight was supposed to take four hours but instead took ten.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 22 March, the majority of 2nd and 3rd Battalions 10th SFG, from Task Force Viking flew from their forward staging area in Constanta, Romania to a location near Irbil aboard six MC-130H Combat Talons.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Several were engaged by Iraqi air defences on the flight into northern Iraq (one was sufficiently damaged enough that it was forced to make an emergency landing at Incirlik Air Base).
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The initial lift had deployed 19 Green Beret ODAs and four ODBs into northern Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Hours after the first of such flights, Turkey did allow the use of its air space and the rest of the 10th SFG infiltrated in.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The preliminary mission was to destroy the base of the Kurdish terrorist group Ansar al-Islam, believed to be linked to al-Qaeda.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Concurrent and follow-on missions involved attacking and fixing Iraqi forces in the north, thus preventing their deployment to the southern front and the main effort of the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Eventually Task Force Viking would number 51 ODAs and ODBs alongside some 60,000 Kurdish Peshmerga militia of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK).
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 26 March, the 173rd Airborne Brigade augmented the invasion's northern front by parachuting into northern Iraq onto Bashur Airfield, controlled at the time by elements of 10th SFG and Kurdish peshmerga.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The fall of Kirkuk on 10 April to the 10th SFG, CIA Paramilitary Teams and Kurdish peshmerga precipitated the 173rd's planned assault, preventing the unit's involvement in combat against Iraqi forces during the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Following the Battle of Haditha Dam, Delta Force handed the dam over to the Rangers and headed north to conduct ambushes along the highway above Tikrit, tying up Iraqi forces in the region and attempting to capture fleeing high-value targets trying to escape to Syria.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 2 April, Delta was engaged by half a dozen armed technicals from the same anti-special forces Fedayeen that had previously fought the SBS.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Two Delta operators were wounded (one serious); the squadron requested an urgent aeromedical evacuation and immediate close-air support as a company of truck-borne Iraqi reinforcements arrived.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The DAPs spotted several Iraqi units and engaged them until they were dangerously low on fuel.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Task Force Viking launched an operation to seize the town of Ain Sifni.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The town was strategically important because it straddles the main highway into Mosul.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Once the town fell, it would be clear for the coalition to advance on Mosul.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODAs from the 3rd and 10th SFG called in airstrikes on the Iraqi garrisons in and around the town, causing many of the Iraqi conscripts to flee.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] By 5 April 2003, there appeared to be only two Iraqi platoons left in the town.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 6 April, ODAs 051, 055, and 056 assaulted the town – ODAs 055 and 056 provided fire support along with Peshmerga heavy weapons teams, while ODA 51 made the actual assault on the town.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] As ODA 51 cautiously advanced on the village, it came under intense fire – the two platoons of Iraqis turned out to be closer to battalion strength and equipped with heavy weapons like 82 mm mortars, anti-aircraft guns, and an artillery piece.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After four hours of F/A-18 airstrikes and constant heavy weapons fire from ODA 055 and 056, the assault force entered Ain Sifni; soon afterward, Iraqi infantry counterattacked, supported by several mortars, attempting to retake the town, but it was beaten back by ODA 51 and the Kurds.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 6 April, ODA 391 and ODA 392 from the 3rd SFG and ODA 044 from 10th SFG with about 150 Kurdish fighters were the main force involved in the Battle of Debecka Pass.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 9 April, nine ODAs from FOB 103 encircled Kirkuk after fierce fighting to capture the ridges overlooking the approaches to the city.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The earlier capture of the nearby city of Tuz had largely broken the will of the Iraqi Army and only the Fedayeen remained in Kirkuk.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The first ODA units entered the city the next day; a week later the 173rd Airborne took over responsibility for the city.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After some minor skirmishes the Fedayeen fled.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Staging out of MSS Grizzly, Delta mounted operations to interdict Ba'ath Party HVTs on Highway 1 (Highway 2 and 4 in western Iraq had been secured by British SAS and Australian SAS teams), on 9 April, the combined team seized an airfield near Tikrit.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The 173rd Brigade would eventually take responsibility for Kirkuk days later, becoming involved in the counterinsurgency fight and remain there until redeploying a year later.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 11 April, an advanced element from FOB 102, numbering no more than thirty Green Berets, advanced into Mosul.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The advance had followed several days of heavy airstrikes on three Iraqi divisions defending Mosul.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 13 April, 3rd Battalion 3rd SFG and a battalion from the 10th Mountain Division were ordered to Mosul to relieve the 10th SFG and their Peshmerga allies.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Further reinforcing operations in northern Iraq, the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit (Special Operations Capable), serving as Landing Force Sixth Fleet, deployed in April to Erbil and subsequently Mosul via Marine KC-130 flights.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The 26 MEU (SOC) maintained security of the Mosul airfield and surrounding area until relief by the 101st Airborne Division.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 21 March, ODA 554 of Bravo Company, 2nd Battalion 5th SFG crossed the border with the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] They later rejoined the other half of the team and fought roving bands of Fedayeen.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The ODAs next mission was to work with a CIA-recruited Sheikh and assist British forces in identifying targets around Basra.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The ODA soon established an informant network, they eventually assisted the British in rounding up some 170 Fedayeen in the city; they were eventually replaced by members of G Squadron 22nd SAS Regiment.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Battle of Haditha Dam occurred on 24 March 2003, Rangers from 3rd Battalion, 75th Ranger Regiment, conducted a combat parachute drop onto H-1 Air Base, securing the site as a staging area for operations in the west.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Delta Force recce operators drove through Iraqi lines around the Haditha Dam on customised ATVs, marking targets for coalition airstrikes resulting in the eventual destruction of a large number of Iraqi armoured vehicles and anti aircraft systems.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Delta's reconnaissance of the dam indicated that a larger force would be needed to seize it, so a request was made and approved for a second Delta squadron from Fort Bragg to be dispatched with a further Ranger battalion, along with M1A1 Abrams tanks from C Company, 2nd Battalion 70th Armor.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] C-17 flew the company from Tallil to H-1 and then to MSS (Mission Support Site) Grizzly – a desert strip established by Delta Force located between Haditha and Tikrit; C Squadron, Delta Force was flown directly to MSS Grizzly.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 1 April, C squadron, Delta Force and 3/75th Ranger Regiment conducted a night-time ground assault in their Pinzgauers and GMVs against the Haditha Dam complex.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Three platoons of Rangers seized the dams' administrative buildings with little initial opposition, while a pair of AH-6M Six Guns orbited overhead.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After daybreak, a Ranger sniper shot and killed 3 Iraqis carrying RPGs on the western side of the dam and Rangers on the eastern side engaged a truck carrying infantry, which led to an hour-long contract.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] South of the dam, another Ranger platoon was securing the dam's power station and electricity transformer against sabotage, another platoon was occupied establishing blocking positions on the main road into the dam complex.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The blocking positions came under the sporadic mortar fire, resulting in the AH-6Ms flying multiple gun runs to silence the mortar positions, another mortar team, firing from a small island was engaged and silenced by a Ranger Javelin team.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Rangers captured an Iraqi forward observer dressed as a civilian after sinking his kayak with .50cal fire, the observer had maps of the Rangers positions.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A-10As engaged nearby electricity transformers successfully blacking out the area, but it resulted in a series of explosions and a resulting fire at the stations that dramatically lit the sky – pinpointing the orbiting helicopters for enemy gunmen.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The SEALs conducted a hasty SSE while the Ranger blocking positions received and returned fire, the AH-6Ms and the aerial snipers continued to engage enemy gunmen while the DAPs pushed further out to ensure no reinforcements approached – engaging and destroying numerous Fedayeen armed technicals.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The SSE took longer than expected owing to the size and maze-like structure of the building, the mission completed after 45 minutes, later tests of the material recovered by DEVGRU showed no evidence of chemical or biological weapons at the Objective Beaver.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Bravo and Charlie companies of 1st Battalion 5th SFG crossed the Kuwait border at H-Hour with ODA 531 using breaching demolition charges to clear a path through the sand berms.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Charlie company's seven ODAs in 35 vehicles took the southeastern operation box of the western desert heading towards the towns of Nukyab, Habbariya and Mudyasis, ODA's 534 and 532 split off to head for the area surrounding Nukyab searching for mobile Scud-B TEL launch sites.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 532 also inserted a mobile weather station that provided planners with vital real time weather updates of the battle space.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Bravo company set out for the central town of Ar Rutba and H-3 Air Base with six ODAs and a support ODB (Operational Detachment Bravo).
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODAs 523 and 524 searched a suspected Scud-B storage facility while ODAs 521 and 525 were tasked with clearing several abandoned airfields, with no sign of Scud launchers, ODA 525 deployed a Special Reconnaissance team to conduct pattern of life surveillance on the town of Ar Rutba.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A two-man team called in a pair of nearby F-16C Fighting Falcons to destroy an Iraqi Army radio direction-finding facility they had identified.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 525 attempted to link up with the two-man reconnaissance team and extract it to safety but large numbers of Iraqi vehicles began driving out of the town to them, the ODAs called in immediate air support.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] While waiting, the reconnaissance team and Target Acquisition Marines fired on the Fedayeen leaders with their suppressed MK12 sniper rifle and contacted ODA 521 (who were clearing suspects east of the town) and they reinforced ODA 525.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Over 100 Fedayeen fighters were killed and four armed technicals were destroyed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] To the west ODA 523 reinforced ODA 524, but ran into a pair of armed technicals on the highway, both were destroyed by the GMVs, the Green Berets ceased fire when a civilian station wagon full of Iraqi children drove into the middle of the firefight.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 522 also identified two Fedayeen armed technicals proceeding down the highway toward ODA 523, they set an ambush for them, destroying the vehicles and killing 15 Fedayeen.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The strategic intent of the US Army Special Forces ODAs had been to shut down the main supply routes and deny access around Ar Rutbah and the strategically important H-3 air base, which was defended by a battalion of Iraqi troops and significant numbers of mobile and static anti aircraft guns.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 521 over watching the highway they were travelling on ambushed the convoy destroying a truck mounted ZU-23, the convoy was thrown into disarray, a sandstorm prevented the ODA calling in airstrikes and the convoy scattered into the desert.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Bravo company 5th SFG and the coalition SOF secured the airfield, finding a Roland surface-to-air missile system, around 80 assorted anti aircraft cannon guns including ZSU-23-4 Shilka, SA-7 grail handheld SAMs and an enormous amount of ammunition.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Additionally, ODA 523 discovered what may have been chemical weapons samples in a laboratory on the grounds of H-3.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODAs guided precision airstrikes on Fedayeen anti aircraft guns on the outskirts of the town and on top of the airstrikes, they also struck large groups of Fedayeen militia with Javelin missiles.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 9 April, nine ODAs secured the main roads into the town and commenced a day of near continuous final airstrikes from fix-wing aircraft and Apache helicopters.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Civilians from the town approached the Green Berets asking them to stop the bombing, the Green Berets struck a deal with the civilians and they entered the town the next day.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A B-52 and 2 F-16Cs flew show of force flights over the town as the Green Berets entered, the Fedayeen blended in with the population.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Within days, the Green Berets helped the town to elect a mayor and set up markets, get sixty percent of the electricity grid working and repair water supplies.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 521 and 525 continued to operate in the region, stopping several trucks carrying foreign fighters, they disarmed them, took their details and warned them not to come back before sending them to Syria; in late May, the teams were replaced by the 3rd Armoured Cavalry Regiment.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Army Special Forces (Green Berets) conducted reconnaissance in the cities of Basra, Karbala and various other locations.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After Sargat was taken, Bravo Company, 3rd Battalion, 10th SFG and CIA paramilitary officers along with their Kurdish allies pushed south towards Tikrit and the surrounding towns of Northern Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Previously, during the Battle of the Green Line, Bravo Company, 3/10 with their Kurdish allies pushed back, destroyed, or routed the 13th Iraqi Infantry Division.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Iraq was the largest deployment of the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 563 worked in support of the US Marines around Al Diwaniyah with local Sheikhs and their militias supported by AV-8Bs and F/A-18s; managing to capture the city of Qwam al Hamza.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The following day ODA 563, their local Sheikh and his militia and a small Force Recon team captured the bridge leading to Diwaniyah and the militia attacked Iraqi positions over the bridge, forcing the Iraqi army and Fedayeen to flee toward Baghdad while being harassed by Marine Corps aircraft.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Private first class Jessica Lynch of the 507th Maintenance Company was seriously injured and captured after her convoy was ambushed by Iraqi forces during the Battle of Nasiriyah.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Initial intelligence that led to her rescue was provided by an informant who approached ODA 553 when it was working in Nasiriyah, the intelligence was passed on and Task Force 20 planned a rescue mission.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The plan called for Task Force Tarawa to conduct a deception mission by seizing the bridges across the Euphrates to draw attention away from the hospital Lynch was held at, an airstrike by U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marine AV-8 Harriers would be conducted against one of the bridges to confuse the opposition further and U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marine AH-1W Cobras were tasked to fly over the area to conceal the sound of incoming SOF helicopters.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Air cover was provided by an AC-130 Spectre and a Marine EA-6B Prowler to jam any enemy SAM systems that might be present.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The main assault force of SEALs would arrive by a ground convoy of AGMS Pandur forearmed vehicles and GMV trucks while the hostage rescue element landed directly on the objective in MH-6 Little Birds.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] At 0100 on 1 April 2003, TF Tarawa commenced their deception mission, CIA elements cut the city's power as the helicopters approached their objective, the AH-6s led the way, behind them the MH-6s dropped off Task Force 20 sniper teams at strategic locations around and on the hospital.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The DAPs and the AH-6s covered the MH-60Ks as they dropped off assault teams on the hospital roof and another by the front door, the ground assault convoy arrived and the assaulters raced inside and onto the second floor where Lynch was located.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] 13 minutes later, a MH-60K touched down near the hospital entrance with a team of PJs and SOAR medics on board and transported Lynch to Tallil where it rendezvoused with a standby medical flight and then onto Kuwait, and finally the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Task Force 20 carried out one of the first successful U.S. prisoner of war rescue missions since World War II.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Three weeks into the invasion, the Army's 3rd Infantry Division, with the 1st Marine Division also present, moved into Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Units of the Iraqi Special Republican Guard led the defence of the city.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The rest of the defenders were a mixture of Republican Guard units, regular army units, Fedayeen Saddam, and non-Iraqi Arab volunteers.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Initial plans were for coalition units to surround the city and gradually move in, forcing Iraqi armor and ground units to cluster into a central pocket in the city, and then attack with air and artillery forces.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This plan soon became unnecessary, as an initial engagement of armored units south of the city saw most of the Republican Guard's assets destroyed and routes in the southern outskirts of the city occupied.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 5 April, Task Force 1–64 Armor of the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Army's 3rd Infantry Division executed a raid, later called the "Thunder Run", to test remaining Iraqi defenses, with 29 tanks and 14 Bradley armored fighting vehicles advancing to the Baghdad airport.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] They met significant resistance, but were successful in reaching the airport, and eventually secured it after heavy fighting.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The next day, another brigade of the 3rd Infantry Division attacked downtown Baghdad and occupied one of the palaces of Saddam Hussein in fierce fighting.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marines also faced heavy shelling from Iraqi artillery as they attempted to cross a river bridge, but the river crossing was successful.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqis managed to inflict some casualties on the U.S. forces near the airport from defensive positions but suffered severe casualties from air bombardment.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Within hours of the palace seizure and with television coverage of this spreading through Iraq, U.S. forces ordered Iraqi forces within Baghdad to surrender, or the city would face a full-scale assault.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Iraqi government officials had either disappeared or had conceded defeat.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 9 April 2003, Baghdad was formally occupied by coalition forces, and a statue of Saddam was toppled.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Much of Baghdad remained unsecured, however, and fighting continued within the city and its outskirts well into the period of occupation.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Saddam had vanished, and his whereabouts were unknown.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 10 April, a rumor emerged that Saddam Hussein and his top aides were in a mosque complex in the Al Az'Amiyah District of Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Three companies of Marines were sent to capture him and came under heavy fire from rocket-propelled grenades, mortars, and assault rifles.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] One Marine was killed and 20 were wounded, but neither Saddam or any of his top aides were found.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S. forces supported by mortars, artillery, and aircraft continued to attack Iraqi forces still loyal to Saddam Hussein and non-Iraqi Arab volunteers.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S. aircraft flying in support were met with Iraqi anti-aircraft fire.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 12 April, by late afternoon, all fighting had ceased.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A total of 34 American soldiers and 2,320 Iraqi fighters were killed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Many Iraqis celebrated the downfall of Saddam by vandalizing the many portraits and statues of him together with other pieces of his cult of personality.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] One widely publicized event was the dramatic toppling of a large statue of Saddam in Baghdad's Firdos Square.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This attracted considerable media coverage at the time.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The fall of Baghdad saw the outbreak of regional, sectarian violence throughout the country, as Iraqi tribes and cities began to fight each other over old grudges.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi cities of Al-Kut and Nasiriyah launched attacks on each other immediately following the fall of Baghdad to establish dominance in the new country, and the U.S.-led coalition quickly found themselves embroiled in a potential civil war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S.-led coalition forces ordered the cities to cease hostilities immediately, explaining that Baghdad would remain the capital of the new Iraqi government.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Nasiriyah responded favorably and quickly backed down; however, Al-Kut placed snipers on the main roadways into town, with orders that invading forces were not to enter the city.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After several minor skirmishes, the snipers were removed, but tensions and violence between regional, city, tribal, and familial groups continued.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Tommy Franks assumed control of Iraq as the supreme commander of the coalition occupation forces.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Shortly after the sudden collapse of the defense of Baghdad, rumors were circulating in Iraq and elsewhere that there had been a deal struck (a "safqua") wherein the U.S.-led coalition had bribed key members of the Iraqi military elite and/or the Ba'ath party itself to stand down.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In May 2003, Franks retired, and confirmed in an interview that the U.S.-led coalition had paid Iraqi military leaders to defect.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The extent of the defections and their effect on the war are unclear.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S.-led coalition troops promptly began searching for the key members of Saddam's government.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] These individuals were identified by a variety of means, most famously through sets of most-wanted Iraqi playing cards.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Later during the military occupation period after the invasion, on 22 July during a raid by the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] 101st Airborne Division and men from Task Force 20, Uday and Qusay Hussein, as well as one of Saddam's grandsons were killed in a massive fire-fight.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Saddam himself was captured on 13 December.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S. special forces had also been involved in the extreme south of Iraq, attempting to occupy key roads to Syria and air bases.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In one case two armored platoons were used to convince Iraqi leadership that an entire armored battalion was entrenched in the west of Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 15 April, U.S. forces took control of Tikrit, the last major outpost in central Iraq, with an attack led by the Marines' Task Force Tripoli.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] About a week later, the Marines were relieved in place by the Army's 4th Infantry Division.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Coalition aircraft flew over 41,000 sorties, of which over 9,000 were tanker sorties.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After the invasion, several factors contributed to the destabilization of Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Paul Bremer issued Coalition Provisional Authority Order Number 2, dissolving the Iraqi Army and other entities of the Ba'athist state.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Ba'athists were excluded from the newly formed Iraqi government.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The first postwar election was won by the United Iraqi Alliance, an electoral coalition composed of mainly Shi’ite groups, which proceeded to ostracize Sunnis.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Shia militia groups pushed Sunnis out of several areas, even emptying entire Sunni neighborhoods in Baghdad during the 2007 troop surge.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The U.S. military established prison camps where disgruntled Iraqis, former Ba'athists, and jihadists met.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi, future leader of the Islamic State, joined al-Qaeda in Iraq (AQI) while detained at Camp Bucca in 2004.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] AQI member Ahmed al-Sharaa, the future leader of al-Nusra Front and Hay'at Tahrir al-Sham, and future Syrian president, was also held there and released in 2008.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] All these factors contributed to Iraq's sectarian violence and the formation and spread of terrorist organizations.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 1 May 2003, Bush gave a speech on the aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln*, announcing the end of major combat operations in the Iraq war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] While he gave the speech, there was a banner hanging behind him that wrote "Mission Accomplished".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The banner, made by White House staff at the request of the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The White House subsequently released a statement that the sign and Bush's visit referred to the initial invasion of Iraq, and disputing the charge of theatrics.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The speech itself noted: "We have difficult work to do in Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] We are bringing order to parts of that country that remain dangerous." Post-invasion Iraq was marked by a long conflict between U.S.-led forces and Iraqi insurgents.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Australia contributed approximately 2,000 Australian Defence Force personnel, including a special forces task group, three warships and 14 F/A-18 Hornet aircraft.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 16 April 2003, Australian special operations forces captured the undefended Al Asad air base west of Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The base would later become the second largest coalition facility post-invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Battle of Umm Qasr was the first military confrontation in the Iraq War, with its objective the capture of the port.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Polish GROM troops supported the amphibious assault on Umm Qasr with the British 3 Commando Brigade of the Royal Marines, and the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After the waterway was de-mined by a Detachment from HM-14 and Naval Special Clearance Team ONE of the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Navy and reopened, Umm Qasr played an important role in the shipment of humanitarian supplies to Iraqi civilians.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In Operation TELIC, British troops participated in the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The 1st Armoured Division was deployed to the Persian Gulf and commanded British forces in the area, securing areas in southern Iraq, including the city of Basra during the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A total of 46,000 troops of all the British services were committed to the operation at its start, including some 5,000 Royal Navy and Royal Fleet Auxiliary sailors and 4,000 Royal Marines, 26,000 British Army soldiers, and 8,100 RAF airmen.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The British special forces deployment was codenamed Operation Row and were known as Task Force 7 under Combined Joint Special Operations Task Force-West (Task Force Dagger).
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The U.S.-led coalition forces toppled the government and captured the key cities of a large nation in only 26 days.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The invasion did require a large army build-up like the 1991 Gulf War, but many did not see combat and many were withdrawn after the invasion ended.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This proved to be short-sighted, however, due to the requirement for a much larger force to combat the irregular Iraqi forces in the Iraqi insurgency.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Army Chief of Staff, recommended "several hundred thousand" troops be used to maintain post-war order, but then Rumsfeld—and especially his deputy, civilian Paul Wolfowitz—strongly disagreed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] General Abizaid later said General Shinseki had been right.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi army, armed mainly with older Soviet and Eastern European built equipment, was overall ill-equipped in comparison to the American and British forces.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Attacks on U.S. supply routes by Fedayeen militiamen were repulsed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqis' artillery proved largely ineffective, and they were unable to mobilize their air force to attempt a defense.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi T-72 tanks, the most powerful armored vehicles in the Iraqi army, were both outdated and ill-maintained, and when they were mobilized they were rapidly destroyed, thanks in part to the coalition air supremacy.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Air Force, Marine Corps and Naval Aviation, and RAF operated with impunity throughout the country, pinpointing heavily defended resistance targets and destroying them before ground troops arrived.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The main battle tanks of American and British forces, the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] M1 Abrams and British Challenger 2, functioned well in the rapid advance across the country.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Despite the many RPG attacks by irregular Iraqi forces, few U.S. and UK tanks were lost, and no tank crew-members were killed by hostile fire, although nearly 40 M1 Abrams were damaged in the attacks.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The only tank loss sustained by the British Army was a Challenger 2 of the Queen's Royal Lancers that was hit by another Challenger 2, killing two crew members.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi army suffered from poor morale, even among the elite Republican Guard.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Entire units disbanded into the crowds upon the approach of invading troops, or actually sought out American and British forces to surrender to.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Many Iraqi commanding officers were bribed by the CIA or coerced into surrendering.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The invasion force did not see the entire Iraqi military thrown against it; American and British units had orders to move to and seize objective target points rather than seek to engage Iraqi units.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This resulted in most regular Iraqi military units emerging from the war without having been engaged, and fully intact, especially in southern Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] It is assumed that most units disintegrated to return to their homes.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Estimates on the number of casualties during the invasion in Iraq vary widely.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Estimates on civilian casualties are more variable than those for military personnel.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Approximately 7,500 civilians were killed during the invasion phase.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Project on Defense Alternatives study estimated that 3,200–4,300 civilians died during the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Fedayeen Saddam militia, Republican Guard, and Iraqi security forces were reported to have executed Iraqi soldiers who tried to surrender on multiple occasions, as well as threatening the families of those who refused to fight.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] One such incident was directly observed during the Battle of Debecka Pass.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Many incidents of Fedayeen fighters using human shields were reported from various towns in Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Iraqi Republican Guard units were also reported to be using human shields.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Some reports indicate that the Fedayeen used ambulances to deliver messages and transport fighters into combat.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 31 March, Fedayeen in a Red Crescent-marked ambulance attacked American soldiers outside Nasiriyah, wounding three.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] During the Battle of Basra, British forces of the Black Watch reported that on 28 March, Fedayeen forces opened fire on thousands of civilian refugees fleeing the city.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After the ambush of the 507th Maintenance Company during the Battle of Nasiriyah on 23 March, the bodies of several Americans soldiers who had been killed in the ambush were shown on Iraqi television.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Some of these soldiers had visible gunshot wounds to the head, leading to speculation that they had been executed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Donald Walters, no evidence has since surfaced to support this scenario and it is generally accepted that the soldiers were killed in action.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Five live prisoners of war were also interviewed on the air, a violation of the Third Geneva Convention.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Sergeant Walters was initially reported to have been killed in the ambush after killing several Fedayeen before running out of ammunition.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] However, an eyewitness later reported that he had seen Walters being guarded by several Fedayeen in front of a building.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Forensics work later found Walters' blood in front of the building and blood spatter suggesting he died from two gunshot wounds to the back at close range.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This led the Army to conclude that Walters had been executed after being captured, and he was posthumously awarded the Prisoner of War Medal in 2004.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] It was alleged in the authorized biography of Pfc.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Jessica Lynch that she was raped by her captors after her capture, based on medical reports and the pattern of her injuries, though this is not supported by Lynch.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Mohammed Odeh al-Rehaief, who later helped American forces rescue Lynch, stated that he saw an Iraqi Colonel slap Lynch while she was in her hospital bed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The staff at the hospital where Lynch was held later denied both stories, saying that Lynch was well cared for.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] While Lynch suffers from amnesia due to her injuries, she denied any mistreatment while in captivity.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Also on 23 March, a British Army engineering unit made a wrong turn near the town of Az Zubayr, which was still held by Iraqi forces.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The unit was ambushed and Sapper Luke Allsopp and Staff Sergeant Simon Cullingworth became separated from the rest.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Both were captured and executed by Iraqi irregular forces.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In 2006, a video of Allsopp lying on the ground surrounded by Iraqi irregular forces was discovered.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] During the Battle of Nasiriyah, Iraqi irregulars feigned surrender to approach an American unit securing a bridge.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After getting close to the soldiers, the Iraqis suddenly opened fire, killing 10 soldiers and wounding 40.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In response, American forces reinforced security procedures for dealing with prisoners of war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marine Sergeant Fernando Padilla-Ramirez was reported missing from his supply unit after an ambush north of Nasiriyah on 28 March.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] His body was later dragged through the streets of Ash-Shatrah and hung in the town square, and later taken down and buried by sympathetic locals.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The corpse was discovered by U.S. forces on 10 April.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In 2023, Amnesty International released a report calling for accountability and reparations for human rights violations perpetrated by the coalition during the invasion and subsequent occupation between 2003 and 2011.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] They cited violations of international humanitarian law including secret prisons, torture and other cruel treatment of detainees, indiscriminate attacks that killed and injured civilians, and forced disappearances.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The report stated that both Bush and Rumsfeld had publicly confessed to involvement in secret detentions and faced no criminal accountability.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The report also noted that despite the conclusions of the International Criminal Court in 2020 that British forces had committed war crimes in Iraq, including deliberate killings, rape and torture, no senior British officials have been held criminally accountable.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Massive looting took place in the days following the 2003 invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] According to U.S. officials, the "reality of the situation on the ground" was that hospitals, water plants, and ministries with vital intelligence needed security more than other sites.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] There were only enough U.S. troops on the ground to guard a certain number of the many sites that ideally needed protection, and so, apparently, some "hard choices" were made.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It was reported that The Iraq Museum was among the looted sites.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The director at the time was archaeologist Nawala Al-Mutawalli.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The FBI was soon called into Iraq to track down the stolen items.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It was found that the initial allegations of looting of substantial portions of the collection were heavily exaggerated.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Initial reports asserted a near-total looting of the museum, estimated at upwards of 170,000 inventory lots, or about 501,000 pieces.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The more recent estimate places the number of stolen pieces at around 15,000, and about 10,000 of them probably were taken in an "inside job" before U.S. troops arrived, according to Bogdanos.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Over 5,000 looted items have since been recovered.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] An assertion that U.S. forces did not guard the museum because they were guarding the Ministry of Oil and Ministry of Interior is disputed by investigator Colonel Matthew Bogdanos in his 2005 book *Thieves of Baghdad*.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Bogdanos notes that the Ministry of Oil building was bombed, but the museum complex, which took some fire, was not bombed.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] He also writes that Saddam Hussein's troops set up sniper's nests inside and on top of the museum, and nevertheless U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Marines and soldiers stayed close enough to prevent wholesale looting.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] András Riedlmayer, a specialist in Islamic architecture at Harvard University, said the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] State Department had asked him for advice before the invasion, and that "everybody warned them that the greatest danger was not from Tomahawk missiles but from looting." Keith D.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] More serious for the post-war state of Iraq was the looting of cached weaponry and ordnance which fueled the subsequent insurgency.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] As many as 250,000 tons of explosives were unaccounted for by October 2004.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Defense Department led to delays in the post-invasion assessment and protection of Iraqi nuclear facilities.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Tuwaitha, the Iraqi site most scrutinized by UN inspectors since 1991, was left unguarded and was looted.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Ancient history professor Zainab Bahrani reported that a helicopter landing pad was constructed in the center of the ancient city of Babylon, and "removed layers of archeological earth from the site.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The daily flights of the helicopters rattle the ancient walls and the winds created by their rotors blast sand against the fragile bricks.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] As of 2007, the invasion was the most widely and closely reported war in military history.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Television network coverage was largely pro-war and viewers were six times more likely to see a pro-war source as one who was anti-war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] *The New York Times* ran a number of articles describing Saddam Hussein's attempts to build weapons of mass destruction.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The 8 September 2002 article titled "U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Says Hussein Intensifies Quest for A-Bomb Parts" was later discredited, leading *The New York Times* to issue a public statement admitting it was not as rigorous as it should have been.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] At the start of the war, as many as 775 reporters and photographers were traveling as embedded journalists.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] These reporters signed contracts with the military that limited what they were allowed to report on.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] When asked why the military decided to embed journalists with the troops, Lt.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Marine Corps replied, "Frankly, our job is to win the war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In 2003, a study released by Fairness & Accuracy in Reporting stated the network news disproportionately focused on pro-war sources and left out many anti-war sources.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] According to the study, 64% of total sources supported the war, while total anti-war sources made up 10% of the media (only 3% of U.S. sources were anti-war).
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The study looked only at six American news networks after 20 March for three weeks.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] A September 2003 poll revealed that 70% of Americans believed Saddam was involved in 9/11.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] 80% of Fox News viewers were found to hold at least one such belief about the invasion, compared to 23% of PBS viewers.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Ted Turner, founder of CNN, charged that Rupert Murdoch was using Fox News to advocate an invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Critics argued that this statistic is indicative of misleading coverage by the U.S. media, since viewers in other countries were less likely to have these beliefs.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Independent media also played a prominent role in covering the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The Indymedia network, among many other independent networks including many journalists from the invading countries, provided reports on the Iraq war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In the U.S., the radio program *Democracy Now* was critical of the invasion, and crimes committed by the U.S. in Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The Israeli Military Censor have released gag orders to Fresh and Rotter news platforms preventing them releasing any information about events and action related to the invasion.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Australian war artist George Gittoes collected independent interviews with soldiers while producing his documentary *Soundtrack To War*.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The Iraq War provided the first time in history that military on the front lines were able to provide direct, uncensored reportage themselves, thanks to blogging software and the reach of the internet.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Dozens of such reporting sites, known as soldier blogs or milblogs, were started during the war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] These blogs were more often than not largely pro-war and stated various reasons why the soldiers and Marines felt they were doing the right thing.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] International coverage of the war differed from coverage in the U.S. in a number of ways.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Arab-language news channel Al Jazeera and the German satellite channel Deutsche Welle featured almost twice as much information on the political background of the war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Al Jazeera also showed scenes of civilian casualties and insurgent attacks rarely seen in the U.S. media.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The central U.S. justification for launching the war was that Saddam's alleged development of nuclear and biological weapons and purported ties to al-Qaeda made his regime a "grave and growing" threat to the U.S. and international community.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] During the lead-up to the war and the aftermath of the invasion, critics cast doubt on the evidence supporting this rationale.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] After the build-up of U.S. troops in neighboring states, Saddam welcomed them back and promised complete cooperation with their demands.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Experienced IAEA inspection teams were already back in Iraq and had made some interim reports on its search for various forms of WMD.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Wilson investigated the contention that Iraq had sought uranium for nuclear weapons in Niger and reported that the contention had no substance.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Similarly, alleged links between Iraq and al-Qaeda were called into question during the lead-up to the war, and were discredited by a 2004 report from U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Senator Carl Levin, which was later corroborated by a 2006 report from the Defense Department's inspector general.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] These reports further alleged that Bush administration officials, particularly former undersecretary of defense Douglas J.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Feith, manipulated evidence to support links between al-Qaeda and Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] An FBI agent who interrogated Saddam at this time stated in 2008 that while Iraq may not have possessed WMDs after the 1990s, Saddam likely intended to restart the WMD program if given the opportunity to do so.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] One of the main questions in the lead-up to the war was whether the UNSC would authorize military intervention in Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It became increasingly clear that this authorization would require significant further weapons inspections.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Many criticized their effort as unwise, immoral, and illegal.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Robin Cook, then-leader of the UK House of Commons and a former foreign secretary, resigned from Blair's cabinet in protest over the UK's decision to invade without UN authorization.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Cook said at the time that: "In principle, I believe it is wrong to embark on military action without broad international support.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In practice, I believe it is against Britain's interests to create a precedent for unilateral military action." In addition, senior government legal advisor Elizabeth Wilmshurst resigned, stating her legal opinion that an invasion would be illegal.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan said in September 2004, "[F]rom our point of view, and from the Charter point of view, [the war] was illegal." This drew immediate criticism from the U.S., and was immediately played down.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The most relevant to this issue is Resolution 678".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Criticisms about the evidence used to justify the war notwithstanding, many opponents of military intervention objected, saying that a diplomatic solution would be preferable, and that war should be reserved as a truly last resort.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] (...) Faithful to its values, it wishes resolutely to act with all the members of the international community.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It believes in our ability to build together a better world." The direct opposition between diplomatic solution and military intervention involving France and the U.S. which was personified by Chirac versus Bush, and later Powell versus de Villepin, became a milestone in the U.S.–France relations.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Anti-French propaganda exploiting Francophobic clichés immediately ensued in the U.S. and UK.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] A call for a boycott on French wine was launched in the U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The *New York Post* claimed that France had forgotten the American "sacrifice" in 1944 France.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] On 20 February 2003, British newspaper *The Sun* published a special issue entitled "Chirac is a worm", which said that "Chirac has become the shame of Europe".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] *The Guardian* wrote that both papers expressed the opinion of their owner, Rupert Murdoch.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Both supporters and opponents of the Iraq War widely viewed it within the context of a post–9/11 world, where the U.S. has sought to make terrorism the defining international security paradigm.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Bush often described the war as a "central front in the war on terror".
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Some critics of the war, particularly within the U.S. military community, argued pointedly against the conflation of Iraq and the war on terror, and criticized Bush for losing focus on the more important objective of fighting al-Qaeda.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In an October 2002 speech, Retired Marine Gen.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Anthony Zinni, former head of Central Command for U.S. forces in the Middle East and State Department's envoy to the Israeli–Palestinian conflict, called Iraq "maybe six or seven," in terms of U.S.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Middle East priorities, adding that "the affordability line may be drawn around five." However, while commander of CENTCOM, Zinni held a very different opinion concerning the threat posed by Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In testimony before the Senate Armed Services Committee in February 2000, Zinni said: "Iraq remains the most significant near-term threat to U.S. interests in the Persian Gulf region.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Besides arguing that Iraq was not the top strategic priority in the war on terrorism or in the Middle East, critics of the war also suggested that it could potentially destabilize the surrounding region.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Prominent among such critics was Brent Scowcroft, who served as National Security Advisor to George H.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In the opinion of Hayder al-Khoei, Iraq was already "destined for chaos" before 2003.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In a March 2003 Gallup poll, the day after the invasion, 76% of Americans supported the military action against Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In a March YouGov poll, 54% of Britons had approved of military action against Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] By 2007, opposition to the Iraq War had increased to 62% among Americans in a USA Today\Gallup poll.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In 2013, a Gallup poll found that 53 percent of Americans surveyed believed the Iraq War was a mistake.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In 2023, an Axios/Ipsos poll found that 61% of Americans believed the U.S made a wrong decision by invading Iraq.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] This campaign featured a variety of new terminology, much of it initially coined by the U.S. government or military.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The military official name for the invasion was Operation Iraqi Freedom.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Also notable was the usage "death squads" to refer to Fedayeen paramilitary forces.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Iraqi officials were given derogatory nicknames – e.g., "Chemical Ali" (Ali Hassan al-Majid), "Baghdad Bob" or "Comical Ali" (Muhammed Saeed al-Sahaf), and "Mrs.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Anthrax" or "Chemical Sally" (Huda Salih Mahdi Ammash).
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Many slogans and terms coined came to be used by Bush's political opponents, or those opposed to the war.
[src:assyria/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Bush's press secretary Ari Fleischer talked about "Operation Iraqi Liberation" in a 2003 press briefing, and "Operation Iraqi Liberation (OIL)" was also used by David Rovics, a popular folk protest singer.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] A series of demonstrations, marches, sit-ins and civil disobedience took place in Iraq from 2019 until 2021.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] It started on 1 October 2019, a date which was set by civil activists on social media, spreading mainly over the central and southern provinces of Iraq, to protest corruption, high unemployment, political sectarianism, inefficient public services and foreign interventionism.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Protests spread quickly, coordinated over social media, to other provinces in Iraq.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] As the intensity of the demonstrations peaked in late October, protesters' anger focused not only on the desire for a complete overhaul of the Iraqi government but also on driving out Iranian influence, including Iranian-aligned Shia militias.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] The government, with the help of Iranian-backed militias responded brutally using live bullets, marksmen, hot water, hot pepper gas and tear gas against protesters, leading to many deaths and injuries.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] The protests, which were the largest of their kind in Iraq since the 2003 American invasion, became known within Iraq as the **October Revolution** (Arabic: ثورة تشرين, romanized: *Thawrat Tishrīn*), and gave rise to the October Protest Movement.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Some called it the **Tuk-Tuk Revolution**, because protesters resisted in tuk-tuks.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] In 2011, protests broke out in various provinces within Iraq demanding the end of corruption, nepotism, and unemployment, while also calling for increased wages and improved public services such as electricity, transportation, health care, education and municipal services.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Protestors faced government suppression, police brutality and arrests.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] These reform demands in the six Sunni-dominant provinces escalated during the 2012–2013 Iraqi protests after Nouri al-Maliki's acts of persecution against Sunni political figures.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] This, in turn, led to protests calling for the overthrow of the sectarian government and redrafting the constitution, as well as a march into Baghdad to occupy the Green Zone.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] These protests were faced with even more government suppression, leading to clashes between security forces and local tribesmen who had alleged support from Ba'ath Party loyalists.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] After reports of the Sunni factions, which were part of the Iraqi insurgency against the American occupation, unifying their powers and taking control over Al Anbar Governorate, the government launched the 2013 Anbar campaign.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] By July 2014, these factions which merged with ISIL had occupied most of Al-Anbar, Ninawa, Salah ad-Din, Kirkuk and Diyala which ignited the War in Iraq (2013–2017).
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Fueled by the lack of progress of Haider al-Abadi's government and state corruption, the leader of the Sadrist Movement, Muqtada al-Sadr, called for a sit-in within the Green Zone in Baghdad to force the government to find serious solutions for corruption.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] On 30 April 2016, thousands of Al-Sadr's followers breached the barricades of the Green Zone and stormed into governmental buildings, including the Iraqi parliament, chasing representatives out of the Green Zone before retreating the day after by the call of Al-Sadr.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Another demonstration broke out in Basra and nearby cities in July 2018 due to deteriorating public utilities, water contamination and lack of electricity and continued for a few months.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Protestors burned down a number of government buildings and parties' headquarters, blocked numerous main streets, tore and burned pictures of Khomeini and Khamenei and even occupied the Al-Najaf and Basra International Airports.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] They were faced with live bullets from security forces causing the death of at least 16 protestors.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Remembering the rise of ISIS during the protests in 2012, these ones avoided sectarian rhetoric.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Foreign intervention by the U.S. and Iran fuelled public anger, in a 2019 poll found that only 22% of Iraqis had a favorable opinion of the United States, 85% viewed the purpose of the 2003 invasion was to divide and plunder Iraq, while 16% had a favorable opinion of Iran.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] On 20 June in Basra demonstrators gathered outside the city's new administrative headquarters to vent their anger about poor basic services and unemployment.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] The old headquarters were burnt down during 2018's months-long protest.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Basra and the surrounding region produce about 90 percent of the country's oil wealth but most of its residents have not benefited from it.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Protesters blamed Basra's authorities for the city's problems, from a lack of job opportunities to unreliable and poor public utilities.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Riot police were deployed at the scene but the protest remained peaceful.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] On 25 September 2019, a group of holders of higher degrees organized a protest in front of the Prime Minister's office in Baghdad, demanding their employment.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] The protest was faced with major suppression from security forces as armoured vehicles separated the demonstrators using hot water and police forces conducted random arrests among them which led to cases of fainting and injuries among the demonstrators.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] This incident was faced with country-wide anger because of the forceful methods that were used by the government towards intellectual demonstrators, along with the violence that was used against female protestors.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Reactions included the Ministry of Interior forming a committee to investigate the incident and demonstrators organizing solidarity protests in many provinces to condemn these methods.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] The holders of higher degrees resumed their protests for three days after the incident, spreading over many southern provinces.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] On 27 September 2019, Iraqi Prime Minister Adil Abdul-Mahdi issued a decision to transfer Abdel-Wahab Al-Saedi, a Lieutenant General at the time, from ICTS to the Ministry of Defence.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Al-Saedi said the decision was an insult to his military rank and that he would rather go to jail than execute this decision.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] This decision caused political figures, including former prime minister Haider al-Abadi and many representatives, to criticize Abdul-Mahdi and call for him to back down from his decisions.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] According to VOA News, Al Saedi's transfer was influenced individually by pro-Iran factions within the Al-Shaabi paramilitary force, said a government official in Iraq who asked to be kept unknown.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] After the decision was made, social media was flooded with Al-Saedi's photos and achievements, calling for Abdul-Mahdi to back down from this injustice and accusing Iran of ordering the Iraqi government to replace every "national hero" in the army with Iranian loyalists.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] In response to this backlash, Abdul-Mahdi said he stands by his decision and that it is a normal routine decision with no political motivations.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Furthermore, after calls for the unveiling of a statue of Al-Saedi in Mosul that was made to immortalize the commander's efforts in the city's liberation, security forces surrounded the statue, prohibiting its unveiling, before it was finally removed by them.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Starting on 25 October 2019, mass protests took place in many cities in Iraq, against corruption and a national government that protestors saw as unaccountable for its actions.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] After the U.S. occupation (2003–11), oligarchs and warlords were perceived to have taken control over Iraq.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] While the country produces more oil than the United Arab Emirates, the oil revenues were seen by protestors as failing to be spent on maintenance of hospitals and roads.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] A widely used slogan in this phase of the protests was: "We want a homeland"—reflecting a longing both for a sense of unity and for a self-determined life in dignity.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Hassan Wahab of the Amal Association human rights group said, "Those [protestors] detained and released are only released on bail.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] As of 23 December 2019, there were 29 assassinated activists related to the protests, most of them were in Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] On 10 January 2020, an Iraqi journalist, Ahmad Abdelsamad, of Dijlah TV and his cameraman, Safaa Ghali, were shot in their car by unidentified gunmen.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] On 21 January, the police stated that Janat Madhi, a 49-year old activist was gunned down by unknown gunmen as she came back home from protests in the southern city of Basra, according to the Urdu Point.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] On 14 August, an activist, Tahseen Osama Al-Shahmani, was shot 20 times at his internet service company in Basra.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] On 19 August, a female activist, Reham Yacoub, was killed and three others were wounded in the city of Basra, when unidentified gunmen opened fire on their car.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] The US Embassy in Baghdad was attacked on the last day of 2019.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] The attack was organized and directed by Iran's proxy leaders Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis, Qais al-Khazali, Hadi al-Amari, and Falih Al-Fayyadh.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] They are seen in the pictures taken on the scene.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis, one of the leaders of the attack on the US Embassy in Baghdad, was condemned and spent years in jail in Kuwait for directing the December 1983 attacks on the US and French embassies there.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] For a long time, Iraqi anti-government protestors tried to enter Green Zone and were brutally suppressed and held back.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] On 31 December, groups of Popular Mobilization Forces (*al-Hashd al-Sha'abi*) entered the Green Zone and went directly toward the American Embassy without being blocked by security forces.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] US President Donald Trump accused Iran of "orchestrating" the attack on the embassy and added that they would be held "fully responsible".
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] In the aftermath, the commander of Iran's Quds Force, Major General Qasem Soleimani, and Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis were tracked down and assassinated in a U.S. drone strike near Baghdad International Airport.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] On 5 January in reaction to these airstrikes the Iraqi parliament called for the expulsion of US troops from the country.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] Muqtada al-Sadr's group stated that it would withdraw its "blue helmets" support for the protests unless the "terrorists responsible" for the lynching were identified.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p01] A protestor's group described the lynching as "a Machiavellian plan aimed at tarnishing the reputation of the peaceful protesters" and that the protestors "had nothing to do with" the lynching event.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] On 21 January, Iraqi police confirmed that three Katyusha rockets landed inside the fortified Green Zone housing government buildings and foreign delegations in Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] The rockets were launched from the Zafaraniyah district outside Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] No group has claimed responsibility for the attack, although Iranian-backed militias have been accused by the US of carrying out similar attacks on the Green Zone over the past few months.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] A rough estimate suggested that the turnout of the protesters had reached 2.5 million.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] Mohammed Allawi, Iraq's PM-designate, held a meeting with several representatives of the protest movement from the various provinces across the country.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] Similar clashes involving al-Sadr's followers attempting to suppress the protests were reported to have taken place across other parts of the country as well, including Karbala, Diwaniyah, Dhi Qar, Baghdad, among others, according to the Kurdistan 24.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] Following the Friday sermon of influential Shia cleric Ali al-Sistani', a lot of anti-government protesters and activists are feeling hopeful and convinced that the protest movement which started in early October, will now regain its momentum, Al Jazeera reported.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] The president of the Kurdistan Regional Government Nechirvan Barzani, has issued a statement condemning the unlawful use of force against peaceful protesters on Wednesday, even though the Kurdish authorities have adopted similar approaches.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] However, the Iranian consulate in Iraq that was set ablaze last year by protesters is now functional, as Visa operations continue, while regular consular services are expected to commence from next week, according to Bloomberg.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] The Najaf police have been charged with the responsibility of providing security and protection for the consulate after its reopening, Lieutenant Najm Al-Saadi added.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] 40 days after Iranian general Qasem Soleimani and Iraq's paramilitary leader were killed by US drones, hundreds of Iraqis in Baghdad came out to the site to mark 40 days remembrance of their death.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] On the same day, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo called Mohammed Allawi to congratulate him on his appointment as the Prime Minister-designate, according to The Sun Herald.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] During the call, both parties assented to the significance of improving the conditions, well-being and security for the people of Iraq by the government.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] The research encompassed thorough video analysis and a 3D reconstruction of incidents near Baghdad's Tahrir Square and Jimhouriya Bridge, according to Urdu Point News.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p02] Based on their findings, the grenades which were produced by Serbians and Iranians, saw to the fatal destruction of at least two dozen demonstrators in the place of the incident since October last year.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Amidst the renewal of fresh anti-government protests in Iraq, the Supreme Judiciary Council on Sunday, issued a statement ordering courts to see to the release of protesters that were arrested since protests began last year.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] The release of the protesters by the Iraqi judiciary was ordered based on demands made by the new prime minister al-Kadhimi, the Washington Post added.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Also, Mustafa al-Kadhimi promoted the Iraqi general Lt.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Abdul Wahab al-Saadi who played a vital role in the war against Islamic State and was subsequently demoted last year by Abdul-Mahdi.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] However, there are no certainties as to whether the protesters who stormed the building are associated with any Iranian-backed organisation in Iraq.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] In the first rallies since Prime Minister Mustafa al-Kadhimi was elected, at least two protesters were killed in Baghdad during overnight demonstrations on 26 July.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] In addition, dozens of people were wounded after officials fired live rounds at the demonstrators who were assembled in Tahrir Square.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Several members of the security forces were also said to have sustained minor injuries, according to the police.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Al-Kadhimi said his administration would investigate Sunday's events and prosecute the guilty party.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] A medical source disclosed on Monday that out of the two protesters who died, one was killed after being shot with a tear gas canister in the head, while the other was shot in the neck, according to Arab News.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Yehia Rasool, spokesman of the Iraqi military revealed in a statement that precise instructions had been issued regarding the unlawful use of force by security forces against demonstrators, except when absolutely necessary.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Separately, protesters in the southern city of Nasiriyah were said to have destroyed the offices of Shiite parties, in response to an explosion that left 11 protesters injured in Nasiriyah's Haboubi Square.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Eyewitnesses on the scene confirmed that the protesters used bulldozers to demolish the offices of the Dawa Party and Badr Organization, although they had already set the buildings on fire.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Subsequently, two people from Sayed Dakhil district in Dhi Qar province were charged with the abduction of Sajjad al-Iraqi, as their arrest warrants were issued by the Iraqi authorities.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] In spite of issuing arrest warrants for the two suspects, the Iraqi counter-terrorism service (ICTS) is yet to make any success in finding Sajjad al-Iraqi even though they have continued their search.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Following the unfortunate incident, Iraqi PM Mustapha al-Kadhimi gave a directive suspending security forces from duty at the airport, according to BBC.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] The US State Department criticized the attack which was launched just after giving out a warning regarding shutting down its embassy in Baghdad, if the Iraqi government is unable to curb attacks against US and other Coalition members.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] The department has also called on the Iraqi authorities to take prompt response and ensure that the perpetrators are brought to face justice.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] A few hours prior to the announcement of the temporary ceasefire deal by the groups, a convoy that was carrying equipment for the U.S.-led coalition, was reportedly targeted with a roadside bomb, according to the Associated Press.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] During the attack which occurred in southern Iraq, one vehicle in the convoy was damaged, Iraq's military disclosed.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] However, no casualties were reported, or those responsible for the attack.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Iraqi high-ranking officials have criticized the attack by the Hashd al-Shaabi protesters and called for an investigation into the attack.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Also, President Barzani has criticized the attack on the KDP offices and urged the Iraqi government to carry out a comprehensive probe into the incident.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Iraq's president, Barham Salih has urged security forces to adhere to the law and avoid applying unlawful use of force against peaceful protesters.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] The Iraqi president further called on the demonstrators, including the security forces to conduct themselves peacefully and not resort to violence.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Also, the United Nations Assistance Mission for Iraq (UNAMI criticized the unlawful use of force that was applied against the demonstrators in Sulaymaniyah district, as the citizens' right to peaceful protest must be ensured.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Meanwhile, the Kurdish Prime Minister Masrour Barzani, has blamed Baghdad for the ongoing violence which erupted due to the delay in payment of salaries in Iraq's northern Kurdish region.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Barzani added that the Iraqi government failed to carry out the budget transfers which were required to make the payments of salary possible.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] However, in a statement made by the U.S.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Secretary of State Mike Pompeo, revealed that there had been at least one Iraqi civilian that was injured.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Meanwhile, the US embassy has urged all Iraqi leaders to ensure that the perpetrators face justice and also take preventive measures from these kinds of attacks.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Thousands of Iraqis demanded United States armed forces pull out of the country in protests in Liberation Square, Baghdad, one year after the American drone strike which killed Qasem Soleimani and Iraq's militia commander, Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] The anniversary of their deaths in Baghdad was also marked in Iran and by supporters in Syria, Lebanon, Yemen and elsewhere in the Middle East.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] The place where both Soleimani and al-Muhandis were killed became a shrine-like area which was sealed off by red ropes, including their pictures in the center by the protesters.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] There haven't been any immediate claims of responsibility by any group yet, for the deadly attack.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Medics have expressed their concerns over the possibility of a drastic increase in the death toll from the initial figures, as security forces continue to guard the site of the blast.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the attack by any group, although Iranian-backed armed groups have claimed responsibility for similar attacks in the past.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Also, no casualties were recorded during the incident, Al Jazeera added.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Meanwhile, as a show of force, unknown gunmen were said to have driven vehicles around Baghdad's fortified Green Zone, following the arrest of Qasim Muslih.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] As a security measure to protect the government and diplomatic missions, the elite Counter-Terrorism Service, including Iraqi security forces were deployed to the Green Zone.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Separately, hours prior to the shooting down of the two drones that targeted Ain al-Assad base, a rocket that was fired over Baghdad's airport was also said to have been shot down.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] There were no casualties or damages recorded, the U.S.-led military coalition's spokesperson in Iraq revealed.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Just a few hours following the attack on the Balad airbase, at least one missile also hit near a military base that is next to the Baghdad International Airport.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] An anonymous security source claimed that five rockets were launched from the nearby Khalis District along the banks of the Tigris River, according to Kurdistan 24.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] However, no immediate claim of responsibility for both attacks was made.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Separately, Iran-backed militia commander Qassem Musleh was released after being arrested for two weeks on terrorism allegations and violations against protesters.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Musleh was released by the judiciary, as there wasn't enough evidence to implicate him on the terrorism charges.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] His release was also said to have followed the arrival of Iranian Gen.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Esmail Ghaani, head of the expeditionary Quds Force in Baghdad.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Musleh received a warm welcome from his supporters at Baghdad's Jadriya Bridge upon his release, as they snapped pictures and rejoiced together.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Also on Friday, a statement from the office of the Iraqi PM Mustafa al-Kadhimi revealed that the director of Iraq's national electricity company had been fired and that the PM has reassured the restoration of electricity.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Meanwhile, three rockets targeted the US embassy in Baghdad's heavily fortified Green Zone, despite earlier attacks on bases housing US troops.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] According to the Iraqi military, the US embassy was not hit during the attack, but three places close to the Green Zone were hit.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] The embassy's defense system, managed to divert one of the rockets that were fired, according to Reuters.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] One of the rockets landed on the outskirts of a residential area, one was close to the headquarters of the National Security Agency, and the other was at a public square.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] Hundreds were injured and two people were killed in **violent clashes in Baghdad** after the parliamentary elections.
[src:assyria/2019-2021-iraqi-protests-p03] These protests had demanded the election results be recounted after alleging election fraud.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Assur, the first Assyrian capital, was founded c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 2600 BC, but there is no evidence that the city was independent until the collapse of the Third Dynasty of Ur, in the 21st century BC, when a line of independent kings starting with Puzur-Ashur I began ruling the city.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Centered in the Assyrian heartland in northern Mesopotamia, Assyrian power fluctuated over time.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The city underwent several periods of foreign rule or domination before Assyria rose under Ashur-uballit I in the early 14th century BC as the Middle Assyrian Empire.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] In the Middle and Neo-Assyrian periods, Assyria was one of the two major Mesopotamian kingdoms, alongside Babylonia in the south, and at times became the dominant power in the ancient Near East.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Assyria was at its strongest in the Neo-Assyrian period, when the Assyrian army was the strongest military power in the world and the Assyrians ruled the largest empire then yet assembled in world history, spanning from parts of modern-day Iran in the east to Egypt in the west.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The remaining Assyrian people, who have survived and preserved their native culture in northern Mesopotamia, were among the first peoples to accept Christianity in the 1st century AD, traditionally held to have been evangelised by St.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Thomas the Apostle, one of the Twelve Disciples of Jesus Christ, and the disciples St.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Mari, going on to develop a unique East Syriac rite and establishing the Church of the East (which would go on to spread Christianity throughout western, central, southeastern, and eastern Asia).
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Ancient Mesopotamian religion persisted at Assur until its final sack in the 3rd century AD, and at certain other holdouts for centuries thereafter.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The triumph of ancient Assyria can be attributed not only to its vigorous warrior-monarchs and skilled soldiers and military institutions, but also to its adeptness in efficiently assimilating and governing conquered territories using inventive and advanced administrative and economic mechanisms.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The developments in warfare and governance introduced by ancient Assyria continued to be employed by subsequent empires and states for centuries.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Ancient Assyria also left a legacy of great cultural significance, particularly through the Neo-Assyrian Empire, making a prominent impression in later Assyrian, Greco-Roman, Persian and Hebrew literary and religious tradition.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] In the Old Assyrian period, when Assyria was merely a city-state centered on the city of Assur, the state was typically referred to as *ālu Aššur* ("city of Ashur").
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] From the time of its rise as a territorial state in the 14th century BC and onward, Assyria was referred to in official documents as *māt Aššur* ("land of Ashur"), marking its shift to being a regional polity.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The first attested use of the term *māt Aššur* is during the reign of Ashur-uballit I (c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 1363–1328 BC), who was the first king of the Middle Assyrian Empire.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Both *ālu Aššur* and *māt Aššur* derive from the name of the Assyrian national deity Ashur.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Ashur probably originated in the Early Assyrian period as a deified personification of Assur itself.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] In the Old Assyrian period the deity was considered the formal king of Assur; the actual rulers only used the style *Išši'ak* ("governor").
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] From the time of Assyria's rise as a territorial state, Ashur began to be regarded as an embodiment of the entire land ruled by the Assyrian kings.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The modern name "Assyria" is of Greek origin, derived from Ασσυρία (*Assuría*).
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The term's first attested use is during the time of the ancient Greek historian Herodotus (5th century BC).
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The Greeks called the Levant "Syria" and Mesopotamia "Assyria", even though the local population, both at that time and well into the later Christian period, used both terms interchangeably to refer to the entire region.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] It is not known whether the Greeks began referring to Mesopotamia as "Assyria" because they equated the region with the Assyrian Empire, long fallen by the time the term is first attested, or because they named the region after the people who lived there, the Assyrians.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Because the term is so "similar to Syria", scholars have been examining since the 17th century whether the two terms are connected.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] And because, in sources predating the Greek ones, the shortened form "Syria" is attested as a synonym for Assyria, notably in Luwian and Aramaic texts from the time of the Neo-Assyrian Empire, modern scholars overwhelmingly support the conclusion that the names are connected.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Both "Assyria" and the contraction, "Syria," are ultimately derived from the Akkadian *Aššur*.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Following the decline of the Neo-Assyrian Empire, the subsequent empires that held dominion over the Assyrian lands adopted distinct appellations for the region, with a significant portion of these names also being rooted in *Aššur*.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The Achaemenid Empire referred to Assyria as *Aθūrā* ("Athura").
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The Sasanian Empire inexplicably referred to Lower Mesopotamia as Asoristan ("land of the Assyrians"), though the northern province of Nōdšīragān, which included much of the old Assyrian heartland, was also sometimes called *Atūria* or *Āthōr*.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] In Syriac, Assyria was and is referred to as *ʾĀthor*.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Agricultural villages in the region that would later become Assyria are known to have existed by the time of the Hassuna culture, c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Though the sites of some nearby cities that would later be incorporated into the Assyrian heartland, such as Nineveh, are known to have been inhabited since the Neolithic, the earliest archaeological evidence from Assur dates to the Early Dynastic Period, c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] During this time, the surrounding region was already relatively urbanized.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] There is no evidence that early Assur was an independent settlement, and it might not have been called Assur at all initially, but rather Baltil or Baltila, used in later times to refer to the city's oldest portion.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The name "Assur" is first attested for the site in documents of the Akkadian period in the 24th century BC.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Through most of the Early Assyrian period (c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 2600–2025 BC), Assur was dominated by states and polities from southern Mesopotamia.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Early on, Assur for a time fell under the loose hegemony of the Sumerian city of Kish and it was later occupied by both the Akkadian Empire and then the Third Dynasty of Ur.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 2025 BC, due to the collapse of the Third Dynasty of Ur, Assur became an independent city-state under Puzur-Ashur I.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Under the Puzur-Ashur dynasty, Assur was home to less than 10,000 people and likely held very limited military power; no military institutions at all are known from this time and no political influence was exerted on neighboring cities.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The city was still influential in other ways; under Erishum I (r. c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 1974–1934 BC), Assur experimented with free trade, the earliest known such experiment in world history, which left the initiative for trade and large-scale foreign transactions entirely to the populace rather than the state.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Royal encouragement of trade led to Assur quickly establishing itself as a prominent trading city in northern Mesopotamia and soon thereafter establishing an extensive long-distance trade network, the first notable impression Assyria left in the historical record.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Among the evidence left from this trade network are large collections of Old Assyrian cuneiform tablets from Assyrian trade colonies, the most notable of which is a set of 22,000 clay tablets found at Kültepe, near the modern city of Kayseri in Turkey.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] As trade declined, perhaps due to increased warfare and conflict between the growing states of the Near East, Assur was frequently threatened by larger foreign states and kingdoms.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The original Assur city-state, and the Puzur-Ashur dynasty, came to an end c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 1808 BC when the city was conquered by the Amorite ruler of Ekallatum, Shamshi-Adad I.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Shamshi-Adad's extensive conquests in northern Mesopotamia eventually made him the ruler of the entire region, founding what some scholars have termed the "Kingdom of Upper Mesopotamia".
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The survival of this realm relied chiefly on Shamshi-Adad's own strength and charisma and thus collapsed shortly after his death c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] After Shamshi-Adad's death, the political situation in northern Mesopotamia was highly volatile, with Assur at times coming under the brief control of Eshnunna, Elam and the Old Babylonian Empire.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] At some point, the city returned to being an independent city-state, though the politics of Assur itself were volatile as well, with fighting between members of Shamshi-Adad's dynasty, native Assyrians and Hurrians for control.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The infighting came to an end after the rise of Bel-bani as king c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Bel-bani founded the Adaside dynasty, which after his reign ruled Assyria for about a thousand years.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Assyria's rise as a territorial state in later times was in large part facilitated by two separate invasions of Mesopotamia by the Hittites.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] An invasion by the Hittite king Mursili I in c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 1595 BC destroyed the dominant Old Babylonian Empire, allowing the smaller kingdoms of Mitanni and Kassite Babylonia to rise in the north and south, respectively.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 1430 BC, Assur was subjugated by Mitanni, an arrangement that lasted for about 70 years, until c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Another Hittite invasion by Šuppiluliuma I in the 14th century BC effectively crippled the Mitanni kingdom.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] After his invasion, Assyria succeeded in freeing itself from its suzerain, achieving independence once more under Ashur-uballit I (r. c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 1363–1328 BC) whose rise to power, independence, and conquests of neighboring territory traditionally marks the rise of the Middle Assyrian Empire (c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Ashur-uballit I was the first native Assyrian ruler to claim the royal title *šar* ("king").
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Shortly after achieving independence, he further claimed the dignity of a great king on the level of the Egyptian pharaohs and the Hittite kings.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Assyria's rise was intertwined with the decline and fall of the Mitanni kingdom, its former suzerain, which allowed the early Middle Assyrian kings to expand and consolidate territories in northern Mesopotamia.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Under the warrior-kings Adad-nirari I (r. c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 1243–1207 BC), Assyria began to realize its aspirations of becoming a significant regional power.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] These kings campaigned in all directions and incorporated a significant amount of territory into the growing Assyrian Empire.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Under Shalmaneser I, the last remnants of the Mitanni kingdom were formally annexed into Assyria.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The most successful of the Middle Assyrian kings was Tukulti-Ninurta I, who brought the Middle Assyrian Empire to its greatest extent.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] His most notable military achievements were his victory at the Battle of Nihriya c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 1237 BC, which marked the beginning of the end of Hittite influence in northern Mesopotamia, and his temporary conquest of Babylonia, which became an Assyrian vassal c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Tukulti-Ninurta was also the first Assyrian king to try to move the capital away from Assur, inaugurating the new city Kar-Tukulti-Ninurta as capital c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The capital was returned to Assur after his death.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 1207 BC was followed by inter-dynastic conflict and a significant drop in Assyrian power.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Tukulti-Ninurta I's successors were unable to maintain Assyrian power and Assyria became increasingly restricted to just the Assyrian heartland, a period of decline broadly coinciding with the Late Bronze Age collapse.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Though some kings in this period of decline, such as Ashur-dan I (r. c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 1114–1076 BC) worked to reverse the decline and made significant conquests, their conquests were ephemeral and shaky, quickly lost again.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 1056–1054 BC) onward, Assyrian decline intensified.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The Assyrian heartland remained safe due to its geographical remoteness.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Since Assyria was not the only state to undergo decline during these centuries, and the lands surrounding the Assyrian heartland were also significantly fragmented, it would ultimately be relatively easy for the reinvigorated Assyrian army to reconquer large parts of the empire.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 934–912 BC), who campaigned in the northeast and northwest, Assyrian decline was at last reversed, paving the way for grander efforts under his successors.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The end of his reign conventionally marks the beginning of the Neo-Assyrian Empire (911–609 BC).
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Through decades of conquests, the early Neo-Assyrian kings worked to retake the lands of the Middle Assyrian Empire.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Since this *reconquista* had to begin nearly from scratch, its eventual success was an extraordinary achievement.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 883–859 BC), the Neo-Assyrian Empire became the dominant political power in the Near East.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] In his ninth campaign, Ashurnasirpal II marched to the coast of the Mediterranean Sea, collecting tribute from various kingdoms on the way.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] A significant development during Ashurnasirpal II's reign was the second attempt to transfer the Assyrian capital away from Assur.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Ashurnasirpal restored the ancient and ruined town of Nimrud, also located in the Assyrian heartland, and in 879 BC designated that city as the new capital of the empire.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Though no longer the political capital, Assur remained the ceremonial and religious center of Assyria.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Ashurnasirpal II's son Shalmaneser III (r.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 859–824 BC) also went on wide-ranging wars of conquest, expanding the empire in all directions.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] After Shalmaneser III's death, the Neo-Assyrian Empire entered into a period of stagnation dubbed the "age of the magnates", when powerful officials and generals were the principal wielders of political power rather than the king.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] This time of stagnation came to an end with the rise of Tiglath-Pileser III (r.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 745–727 BC), who reduced the power of the magnates, consolidated and centralized the holdings of the empire, and through his military campaigns and conquests more than doubled the extent of Assyrian territory.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The most significant conquests were the vassalization of the Levant all the way to the Egyptian border and the 729 BC conquest of Babylonia.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The Neo-Assyrian Empire reached the height of its extent and power under the Sargonid dynasty, founded by Sargon II (r.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Under Sargon II and his son Sennacherib (r.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 705–681 BC), the empire was further expanded and the gains were consolidated.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] In 706 BC, Sargon II relocated the capital to the newly constructed city of Dur-Sharrukin.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The following year, Sennacherib transferred the capital to Nineveh, which he extensively expanded and renovated.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] He may even have been responsible for the construction of the Hanging Gardens there—one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The 671 BC conquest of Egypt under Esarhaddon (r.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 681–669 BC) brought Assyria to its greatest ever extent.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] 669–631 BC), the Neo-Assyrian Empire swiftly collapsed.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] One of the primary reasons was the inability of the Neo-Assyrian kings to resolve the "Babylonian problem"; despite many attempts to appease Babylonia in the south, revolts were frequent all throughout the Sargonid period.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The revolt of Babylon under Nabopolassar in 626 BC, in combination with an invasion by the Medes under Cyaxares in 615/614 BC, led to the Medo-Babylonian conquest of the Assyrian Empire.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Assur was sacked in 614 BC and Nineveh fell in 612 BC.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The last Assyrian ruler, Ashur-uballit II, tried to rally the Assyrian army at Harran in the west but he was defeated in 609 BC, marking the end of the ancient line of Assyrian kings and of Assyria as a state.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Despite the violent downfall of the Assyrian Empire, Assyrian culture continued to survive through the subsequent post-imperial period (609 BC – c.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The Assyrian heartland experienced a dramatic decrease in the size and number of inhabited settlements during the rule of the Neo-Babylonian Empire founded by Nabopolassar; the former Assyrian capital cities Assur, Nimrud and Nineveh were nearly completely abandoned.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Throughout the time of the Neo-Babylonian and later Achaemenid Empire, Assyria remained a marginal and sparsely populated region.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Toward the end of the 6th century BC, the Assyrian dialect of the Akkadian language went extinct, having toward the end of the Neo-Assyrian Empire already largely been replaced by Aramaic as a vernacular language.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Under the empires succeeding the Neo-Babylonians, from the late 6th century BC onward, Assyria began to experience a recovery.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Under the Achaemenids, most of the territory was organized into the province Athura (*Aθūrā*).
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The organization into a single large province, the lack of interference of the Achaemenid rulers in local affairs, and the return of the cult statue of Ashur to Assur soon after the Achaemenids conquered Babylon facilitated the survival of Assyrian culture.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Under the Seleucid Empire, which controlled Mesopotamia from the late 4th to mid-2nd century BC, Assyrian sites such as Assur, Nimrud and Nineveh were resettled, and a large number of villages were rebuilt and expanded.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] After the Parthian Empire conquered the region in the 2nd century BC, the recovery of Assyria continued, culminating in an unprecedented return to prosperity and revival in the 1st to 3rd centuries AD.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The region was resettled and restored so intensely that the population and settlement density reached heights not seen since the Neo-Assyrian Empire.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The region was under the Parthians primarily ruled by a group of vassal kingdoms, including Osroene, Adiabene and Hatra.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Though in some aspects influenced by Assyrian culture, these states were for the most part not ruled by Assyrian rulers.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] Assur itself flourished under Parthian rule.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] From around or shortly after the end of the 2nd century BC, the city may have become the capital of its own small semi-autonomous Assyrian realm, either under the suzerainty of Hatra, or under direct Parthian suzerainty.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] On account of the resemblance between the stelae by the local rulers and those of the ancient Assyrian kings, they may have seen themselves as the restorers and continuators of the old royal line.
[src:assyria/assyria-p01] The ancient Ashur temple was restored in the 2nd century AD.
